{"title_page": "Walter Reuther", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{short description|Labor union leader}}\n{{lead too long|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = Walter Reuther Department of Labor Hall of Honor.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Portrait of Reuther\n| birth_name = Walter Philip Reuther\n| birth_date = September 1, 1907\n| birth_place = [[Wheeling, West Virginia]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1970|5|9|1907|9|1}}\n| death_place = [[Pellston, Michigan]], U.S.\n| death_cause = Plane crash\n| other_names = \n| known_for = [[labor movement]], [[civil rights movement]]\n| office1 = 4th President of the [[United Automobile Workers]]\n| term_start1 = 1946\n| term_end1 = 1970\n| predecessor1 = [[R.J. Thomas]]\n| successor1 = [[Leonard F. Woodcock]]\n| signature = Walter_Reuther_Signature_Darker_and_Transparent_Background.xcf\n| office2 = 3rd President of the [[Congress of Industrial Organizations]]\n| term_start2 = 1952\n| term_end2 = 1955\n| predecessor2 = [[Philip Murray]]\n| successor2 = [[George Meany]]\n| occupation = [[Labor leader]]\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| awards = {{ubl|[[File:Presidential Medal of Freedom (ribbon).png|border|23px]] [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] (Posthumous; 1995)|[[Weizmann Institute of Science|Weizmann Award]]|[[Eugene V. Debs Award]]|[[Labor Hall of Honor]]|[[Automotive Hall of Fame]]}}\n| nationality = American\n| education = [[Wayne State University]] (withdrew)\n| spouse = {{marriage | May Wolf |1936}}\n| children = {{hlist|Linda|Elisabeth}}\n| parents = {{ubl|Valentine Reuther|Anna Stocker}}\n| relatives = {{ubl|[[Victor G. Reuther|Victor Reuther]]|Roy Reuther|Ted Reuther|Christine Reuther}}\n}}\n\n'''Walter Philip Reuther''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|u\u02d0|\u03b8|\u0259r}}; September 1, 1907 \u2013 May 9, 1970) was an American leader of [[Labor unions in the United States|organized labor]] and [[Civil rights movements|civil rights]] activist who built the [[United Automobile Workers]] (UAW) into one of the most [[Progressivism|progressive]] labor unions in American history.<ref name=\"United States Department of Labor\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dol.gov/general/aboutdol/hallofhonor/1990_reuther|title=Hall of Honor Inductee: Walter P. Reuther|date=December 9, 2015|work=United States Department of Labor|access-date=February 22, 2018|language=en}}</ref> He saw labor movements not as narrow special interest groups but as instruments to advance [[social justice]] and [[human rights]] in democratic societies.<ref name=\"United States Department of Labor\"/> He leveraged the UAW's resources and influence to advocate for [[United States labor law|workers' rights]], civil rights, [[women's rights]], [[universal health care]], [[Education in the United States|public education]], [[affordable housing]], [[Environmental movement in the United States|environmental stewardship]] and [[Nuclear proliferation|nuclear nonproliferation]] around the world.<ref name=\"United States Department of Labor\"/> He survived two attempted assassinations, including one at home where he was struck by a 12-gauge shotgun blast fired through his kitchen window.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://reuther100.wayne.edu/bio.php?pg=3|title=Walter P. Reuther|website=reuther100.wayne.edu|access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> He was the fourth and longest serving president of the UAW, serving from 1946 until his untimely death in 1970.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aflcio.org/about/history/labor-history-people/walter-reuther|title=Walter Reuther {{!}} AFL-CIO|website=aflcio.org|language=en|access-date=March 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA powerful ally of [[Martin Luther King Jr.|Martin Luther King, Jr.]] and the civil rights movement,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://billmoyers.com/content/meet-the-march-organizers/9/|title=Meet the 1963 March on Washington Organizers {{!}} BillMoyers.com|work=BillMoyers.com|access-date=February 25, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Reuther marched with King in [[Detroit Walk to Freedom|Detroit]], [[Selma to Montgomery marches|Selma]],<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.uawregion8.net/Activist-HOF/WReuther.htm|title=Region 8|website=www.uawregion8.net|access-date=March 1, 2018}}</ref> [[Birmingham campaign|Birmingham]],<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://kinginstitute.stanford.edu/encyclopedia/reuther-walter-philip|title=Reuther, Walter Philip|website=kinginstitute.stanford.edu|access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref> [[Selma to Montgomery marches|Montgomery]],<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Putting the World Together: My Father Walter Reuther: The Liberal Warrior|last=Dickmeyer, Reuther|first=Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=Living Force|year=|isbn=9780975379219|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/339 339]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/339}}</ref> and [[March Against Fear|Jackson]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://reuther.wayne.edu/node/7829|title=Walter P. Reuther Library (225427) Civil Rights, Demonstrations, \"Meredith March Against Fear,\" Mississippi, 1966|website=reuther.wayne.edu|language=en|access-date=March 1, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=Putting the World Together: My Father Walter Reuther: The Liberal Warrior|last=Dickmeyer|first=Reuther, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Publishing|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Michigan|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/350 350]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/350}}</ref> When King and others including children were jailed in [[Birmingham campaign|Birmingham, Alabama]], and King authored his famous [[Letter from Birmingham Jail]], Reuther arranged $160,000 for the protestors' release.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|title=Putting the World Together: My Father Walter Reuther: The Liberal Warrior|last=Dickmeyer|first=Reuther, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Publishing|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Michigan|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/237 237]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/237}}</ref> He also helped organize and finance the [[March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom|March on Washington]] on August 28, 1963, delivering remarks from the steps of the [[Lincoln Memorial]] shortly before King gave his historic \"[[I Have a Dream]]\" speech on the [[National Mall]].<ref name=\":2\"/><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=http://billmoyers.com/content/meet-the-march-organizers/9/|title=Meet the 1963 March on Washington Organizers {{!}} BillMoyers.com|work=BillMoyers.com|access-date=February 25, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> He served on the board of directors for the [[NAACP|National Association for the Advancement of Colored People]] (NAACP)<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://whospeaks.library.vanderbilt.edu/sites/default/files/WilkinsToWarren27Nov64.pdf|title=NAACP letterhead from November 24,1964, listing board members|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> and was one of the founders of [[Americans for Democratic Action]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://adaction.org/ada-history/|title=ADA's History \u2013 Americans for Democratic Action|work=Americans for Democratic Action|access-date=March 1, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> An early supporter of [[Cesar Chavez]] and the [[United Farm Workers]], he asked [[Robert F. Kennedy]] to visit and support Chavez.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The 100 greatest Americans of the 20th century : a social justice hall of fame|last=1948-|first=Dreier, Peter|date=2012|publisher=Nation Books|isbn=9781568586816|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/339 339]|oclc=701015405|url=https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/339}}</ref> A lifetime environmentalist, Reuther played a critical role in funding and organizing the first [[Earth Day]] on April 22, 1970.<ref name=\"Grist\">{{Cite news|url=https://grist.org/article/2010-04-21-labor-and-environmentalists-have-been-teaming-up-since-the-first/full/|title=Labor and environmentalists have been teaming up since the first Earth Day|date=April 22, 2010|work=Grist|access-date=February 24, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> According to [[Denis Hayes]], the principal national organizer of the first Earth Day, \"Without the UAW, the first Earth Day would have likely flopped!\"<ref name=\"Grist\"/>\n\nAs the leader of five million autoworkers including retirees and their families,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/383 383]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/383}}</ref> Reuther was influential inside the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The reckoning|first=David|last=Halberstam|date=1986|publisher=Morrow|isbn=9780688048389|edition=  1st|location=New York|pages=345|oclc=13861133}}</ref> During [[World War II]], President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] frequently consulted Reuther, referring to him as \"my young red-headed engineer.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The 100 greatest Americans of the 20th century : a social justice hall of fame|last=1948\u2013|first=Dreier, Peter|date=2012|publisher=Nation Books|isbn=9781568586816|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/233 233]|oclc=701015405|url=https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/233}}</ref> He was considered by [[John F. Kennedy]] for Vice President in 1960.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/3491219/behind-the-picture-jfk-and-rfk-los-angeles-july-1960/|title=Head to Head: JFK and RFK, Los Angeles, July 1960|last=Cosgrove|first=Ben|website=Time|language=en-us|access-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> Following the [[Bay of Pigs Invasion|Bay of Pigs]] in 1961, JFK sent Reuther to Cuba to negotiate a prisoner exchange with [[Fidel Castro]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/25/business/media/robert-boyd-dead.html|title=Robert Boyd, Journalist Whose Reporting Shifted an Election, Dies at 91|last=Roberts|first=Sam|date=September 25, 2019|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 5, 2019}}</ref> He was instrumental in spearheading the creation of the [[Peace Corps]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Walter Reuther|last=1943\u2013|first=Carew, Anthony|date=1993|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=9780719021886|location=Manchester|pages=101|oclc=27676666}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stanforddailyarchive.com/cgi-bin/stanford?a=d&d=stanford19640407-02.2.6|title=The Stanford Daily 7 April 1964 \u2014 The Stanford Daily|website=stanforddailyarchive.com|access-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The UAW and the heyday of American liberalism, 1945\u20131968|last=1960\u2013|first=Boyle, Kevin|date=1995|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801485381|location=Ithaca|pages=[https://archive.org/details/uawheydayofameri0000boyl/page/144 144]|oclc=32626436|url=https://archive.org/details/uawheydayofameri0000boyl/page/144}}</ref> and in marshaling support for the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/18/books/review/an-idea-whose-time-has-come-and-the-bill-of-the-century.html|title='An Idea Whose Time Has Come' and 'The Bill of the Century'|last=Boyle|first=Kevin|date=May 15, 2014|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 8, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"1948\u20132012 235\">{{Cite book|title=The 100 greatest Americans of the 20th century : a social justice hall of fame|last=1948\u2013|first=Dreier, Peter|date=2012|publisher=Nation Books|isbn=9781568586816|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/235 235]|oclc=701015405|url=https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/235}}</ref> the [[Voting Rights Act of 1965]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=The 100 greatest Americans of the 20th century : a social justice hall of fame|last=1948-|first=Dreier, Peter|date=2012|publisher=Nation Books|isbn=9781568586816|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/235 235]|oclc=701015405|url=https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/235}}</ref> [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] and [[Medicaid]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ssa.gov/history/LBJ/lbj.html|title=Social Security History|website=www.ssa.gov|language=en|access-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> and the [[Fair Housing Act]].<ref name=\"1948\u20132012 235\"/> He met weekly in 1964 and 1965 with President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] at the [[White House]] to discuss policies and legislation for the [[Great Society]] and [[War on Poverty]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/248 248]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/248}}</ref> The [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] was wary of Reuther, leading presidential candidate [[Richard Nixon]] to say about John F. Kennedy during the 1960 election, \"I can think of nothing so detrimental to this nation than for any President to owe his election to, and therefore be a captive of, a political boss like Walter Reuther.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Reuther|last=Frank.|first=Cormier|date=1970|publisher=Prentice-Hall|others=Eaton, William J.|isbn=9780137793143|location=Englewood Cliffs, N.J.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/376 376]|oclc=91809|url=https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/376}}</ref> Conservative politician [[Barry Goldwater]] declared that \"[Reuther] was more dangerous to our country than Sputnik or anything Soviet Russia might do.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The conscience of a liberal|last=Krugman|first=Paul R.|date=2007|publisher=W.W. Norton & Co|isbn=9780393333138|edition=1st|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/conscienceoflib00krug/page/111 111]|oclc=154706837|url=https://archive.org/details/conscienceoflib00krug/page/111}}</ref>\n\nReuther was posthumously awarded the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] in 1995 by President [[Bill Clinton]], who remarked at the ceremony, \"Walter Reuther was an American visionary so far ahead of his times that although he died a quarter of a century ago, our Nation has yet to catch up to his dreams.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Public Papers of the Presidents of the United States, William J. Clinton|last=|first=|publisher=United States Government Printing Office|year=1996|isbn=|location=|pages=Book II, page 1516}}</ref> Reuther was recognized by [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']] Magazine as one of the 100 most influential people of the 20th century.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,26473,00.html|title=TIME 100 Persons of The Century|date=June 6, 1999|work=Time|access-date=February 22, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0040-781X}}</ref> [[Murray Kempton]], a Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist, wrote, \"Walter Reuther is the only man I have ever met who could reminisce about the future.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oOo7DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA562&lpg=PA562&dq=Walter+Reuther+is+the+only+man+I+have+met+who+could+reminisce+about+the+future&source=bl&ots=ZmkISezp6v&sig=ACfU3U24zZeRD0gZsbq0ttsOxZCkY5tiHg&hl=en&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiVi6WS_f7mAhVOrp4KHT0qD7kQ6AEwCnoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=Walter%20Reuther%20is%20the%20only%20man%20I%20have%20met%20who%20could%20reminisce%20about%20the%20future&f=false|title=Whip: Leading the Progressive Battle During the Rise of the Right|last=Bonier|first=David|date=|website=www.presidency.ucsb.edu|page=562|url-status=live|archive-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oOo7DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA562&lpg=PA562&dq=Walter+Reuther+is+the+only+man+I+have+met+who+could+reminisce+about+the+future&source=bl&ots=ZmkISezp6v&sig=ACfU3U24zZeRD0gZsbq0ttsOxZCkY5tiHg&hl=en&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiVi6WS_f7mAhVOrp4KHT0qD7kQ6AEwCnoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=Walter%20Reuther%20is%20the%20only%20man%20I%20have%20met%20who%20could%20reminisce%20about%20the%20future&f=false|archive-date=|access-date=February 26, 2018}}</ref> [[A. H. Raskin]], labor editor of [[The New York Times]], wrote, \"If the speed of a man's mind could be measured in the same way as the speed of his legs, Walter Reuther would be an Olympic champion.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/88 88]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/88}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/GPO-CRECB-1970-pt16/pdf/GPO-CRECB-1970-pt16-4-1.pdf|title=Congressional Record, House of Representatives, Statement by Irving Bluestone|last=|first=|date=June 29, 1970|website=U.S. Government Publishing Office|page=21886|accessdate=March 4, 2018}}</ref> [[George W. Romney|George Romney]], Governor of Michigan, once said, \"Walter Reuther is the most dangerous man in Detroit because no one is more skillful in bringing about the revolution without seeming to disrupt the existing forms of society.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The 100 greatest Americans of the 20th century : a social justice hall of fame|last=1948\u2013|first=Dreier, Peter|date=2012|publisher=Nation Books|isbn=9781568586816|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/234 234]|oclc=701015405|url=https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/234}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nReuther was born on September 1, 1907, in [[Wheeling, West Virginia]], to Anna (n\u00e9e Stocker) and Valentine Reuther, who were [[German-Americans]].<ref>http://www.biography.com/people/walter-reuther-21402271</ref> His father Valentine was a horse-drawn beer wagon driver and [[Socialist Party of America|Socialist]] union organizer who at age 11 had emigrated from [[Germany]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/14 14]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/14}}</ref> Walter was one of five children, oldest to youngest: Ted, Walter, Roy, Victor, Christine. Valentine would facilitate debates every Sunday for his sons, training them to think on their feet about social issues of the day such as yellow journalism, child labor, women's suffrage, and civil rights.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW : a memoir|last=Reuther|first=Victor G.|date=1978|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=9780395275153|edition=  UAW special|location=Boston|pages=36\u201337|oclc=26295254}}</ref> Reuther later recalled, \"At my father's knee we learned the philosophy of trade unionism. We got the struggles, the hopes and the aspirations of working people every day.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://reuther100.wayne.edu/bio.php|title=Walter P. Reuther|website=reuther100.wayne.edu|access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref> As a child, he and Victor accompanied their father on a visit to a jail to meet [[Eugene V. Debs]], who was being incarcerated for his pacifism during World War I.<ref name=\"Raskin\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/06/13/archives/the-brothers-reuther.html|title=The Brothers Reuther|last=Raskin|first=A. H.|date=June 13, 1976|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 18, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>[[File:Reuther brothers busts.jpg|thumb|The Reuther brothers' busts at the Walter and May Reuther UAW Family Education Center in northern Michigan. From left to right, Roy Reuther, Walter Reuther, and Victor Reuther.]]\n\nThe Reuthers were frugal and learned not to waste. To save money, Walter's mother Anna would make underwear for her sons out of used flour sacks.<ref name=\"Halberstam 1986 339\">{{Cite book|title=The reckoning|last=Halberstam|first=David|date=1986|publisher=Morrow|year=|isbn=9780688048389|edition=1st|location=New York|pages=336|oclc=13861133}}</ref> When Valentine was partially blinded by an exploding bottle, Walter began doing odd jobs to bring in family income at the age of nine. He later dropped out of high school during his junior year and worked in a local factory to help support the family.<ref name=\"Halberstam 1986 339\"/> He learned firsthand about inadequate worker safety when a 400 pound die that he and three other men were lifting fell and severed his big toe.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/18 18]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/18}}</ref>\n\nFrom an early age, the Reuther boys received lessons on racism. One day they saw local boys throwing rocks at black people being transported north through their hometown in open railways cars. Their father gave them a stern warning to never treat another human being like that. The Reuther boys never forgot that lesson, spending the rest of their lives fighting for racial and economic equality for all people.<ref>{{Cite book|title=LIFE AND TIMES OF WALTER REUTHER.|last=JAMES.|first=TENEYCK|date=2016|publisher=PAGE PUBLISHING, INC|isbn=9781683482086|location=[S.l.]|pages=264|oclc=975986306}}</ref>\n\n=== Left home for Detroit ===\nIn 1927, at the age of 19, Reuther left Wheeling for Detroit and argued himself into an expert [[tool and die maker]] job at [[Ford Motor Company]] that required 25 years experience. The foreman was baffled that at his young age he could read blueprints and dies, becoming one of the highest paid mechanics in the factory.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW : a memoir|last=Reuther|first= Victor G |date=1978|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=9780395275153|edition=  UAW special |location=Boston|pages=46\u201348|oclc=26295254}}</ref> He finished high school while working at Ford and enrolled at Detroit City College, which is today known as [[Wayne State University]]. In 1932, he was fired for organizing a rally for [[Norman Thomas]] who was running for President of the United States as the nominee for the [[Socialist Party of America]]. His official Ford employment record states that he quit voluntarily, but Reuther himself maintained that he was fired for his increasingly visible socialist activities.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The most dangerous man in Detroit : Walter Reuther and the fate of American labor|last=Nelson.|first=Lichtenstein|date=1995|publisher=Basic Books|isbn=9780465090808|location=New York, NY|oclc=32468620|url=https://archive.org/details/mostdangerousman00lich}}</ref> Regardless, Walter and Victor decided it was the perfect time to fulfill their childhood dream and travel the world.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/25 25]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/25}}</ref>\n\n=== European trip ===\n\nWhen [[Henry Ford]] retired the [[Ford Model T|Model T]] in 1927, he sold the production mechanisms to Russia and American workers who knew how to operate the equipment were needed. Walter and Victor were promised work teaching Russian workers how to run the machines and assembly line. With that employment assurance, the brothers embarked on a three-year adventure, first bicycling through Europe, then working in the auto plant in [[Gorky, Russia]] where the unheated factories were often 30\u201340 degrees Fahrenheit below zero. He frequently wrote letters to the Moscow Daily News criticizing the many inefficiencies associated with how the communists operated the plants.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW : a memoir|last=Reuther |first= Victor G.|date=1978|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=9780395275153|edition=  UAW special |location=Boston|pages=88\u2013103|oclc=26295254}}</ref>\n\nAfter almost two years in Russia, the brothers travelled through Turkey, Iran, India, and China. After crossing the China Sea, they finished their Far East tour by bicycling throughout Japan. Finally, after being gone from home for almost three years, they found work for passage on the steamship President Harding to San Francisco and hurried back to Detroit where their brother Roy was already deeply involved with organizing autoworkers. Walter later stated the world tour taught him that \"all people long for the same basic human goals of a job with some degree of security, greater opportunity for their children, and of course, freedom. We felt we could make a contribution by helping American workers build strong and democratic labor unions. That's why we went into the labor movement.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/34 34]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/34}}</ref>\n\n===Political affiliation===\nBefore joining the Democratic Party, Reuther was a member of the Socialist Party of America. And, although Reuther always denied it, people including [[J. Edgar Hoover]], have suspected that at one time he was a member of the Communist Party.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Walter Reuther|last=Carew|first=Anthony|publisher=Manchester University Press|year=1993|isbn=071902188X|location=|pages=86}}</ref> On this subject, Reuther said in 1938, \"I am not and never have been a member of the Communist Party nor a supporter of its policies nor subject to its control or influence in any way.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Devinatz|first=Victor|date=2002|title=Reassessing The Historical UAW: Walter Reuther's Affiliation with the Communist Party and Something of Its Meaning \u2014 A Document of Party Involvement, 1939|url=http://www.lltjournal.ca/index.php/llt/article/view/5257|journal=Labour / Le Travail|volume=49|pages=225\u2013226|via=}}</ref> Nevertheless, people have suspected that he may have paid dues to the Communist Party for some months in 1935-36 and one source listed him as attending a Communist Party planning meeting as late as February 1939.<ref>Victor G. Devinatz, \n \"Reassessing the Historical UAW: Walter Reuther's Affiliation with the Communist Party and Something of Its Meaning: A Document of Party Involvement, 1939.\" ''Labour/Le Travail'' 49 (2002): 223-245. [https://journals.lib.unb.ca/index.php/LLT/article/viewFile/5257/6127 online] and also [https://www.jstor.org/stable/25149221 online at JSTOR] Devinatz says that he must have left the Party later in 1939.</ref> Reuther did cooperate with the Communists in the mid 1930s; this was the period of the [[Popular Front]], and the Communist Party agreed with him on internal issues of the UAW; but his associations were with anti-Stalinist Socialists.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/walterreuthermos00lich|url-access=registration|title=Walter Reuther: The Most Dangerous Man in Detroit|publisher=University of Illinois Press|author=Nelson Lichtenstein|year=1997|pages=[https://archive.org/details/walterreuthermos00lich/page/54 54]\u201356}}</ref><ref>Nelson Lichtenstein states, \" Reuther worked very closely with the Communists during this period, but he did not actually join the party.\" in Lichtenstein \"Reuther the Red?\" ''Labour/Le Travail'' 51 (2003) pp 165=69 at p 165.</ref> Reuther remained active in the Socialist Party and in 1937 failed in his attempt to be elected to the Detroit City Council when the AFL and blacks opposed his CIO ticket.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/walterreuthermos00lich|url-access=registration|title=Walter Reuther|publisher=University of Illinois Press|author=Lichtenstein|year=1997|pages=[https://archive.org/details/walterreuthermos00lich/page/87 87]\u201391}}</ref> However, impressed by the efforts by President Franklin D. Roosevelt to tackle inequality, he eventually joined the Democratic Party.\n\n== United Automobile Workers ==\n=== First victory against automobile companies ===\nUpon returning from Europe to Detroit, Reuther hitchhiked to [[South Bend, Indiana]] to attend the second annual convention as a delegate of the fledgling UAW. Upon his return he became president of newly formed Local 174 on Detroit's west side and with brother Victor, led the first successful strike against the automotive giants at Kelsey Hayes, which supplied brake drums and wheels to Ford Motor Company. The main complaint was the speed-up of the assembly line was intolerable. Workers were losing limbs and even their own lives trying in vain to keep up with the ever-increasing speed of the assembly line. It was December 1936 when the workers pulled a surprise strike and sat down in the plant refusing to leave until management negotiated with their representative, Walter Reuther.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Reuther|last=Frank.|first=Cormier|date=1970|publisher=Prentice-Hall|others=Eaton, William J.|isbn=9780137793143|location=Englewood Cliffs, N.J.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/70 70\u201373]|oclc=91809|url=https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/70}}</ref>\n\nWhen management tried to enter the plant to remove the machinery, thousands of sympathizers swarmed the sidewalks and blocked the doorways. Ford needed those brake drums and wheels badly and after 10 days of striking the sides settled. The first major UAW victory to unionize the auto factories was won. Upon Reuther's insistence, women won equal pay for equal work: 75 cents an hour. The speed-up of the assembly line was slowed down and the company could not fire a worker for joining the union. UAW Local 174's membership expanded from 200 before the strike to 35,000 within the next year.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/39 39\u201341]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/39}}</ref>\n\n=== General Motors ===\nIn 1936, [[General Motors]] (GM) was the largest corporation in the world and held many plants in [[Flint, Michigan]], about 60 miles north of Detroit. Reuther's brother, Roy, was already in Flint drawing up strategy plans and organizing workers to shut down the automaker until it would recognize the rights of the workers to unionize. The strike began on New Year's Eve, December 31, 1936 when the workers sat down in the plants and refused to leave. General Motors retaliated by turning off the heat in the plant.\n\nIn solidarity with the Flint strikers, Reuther led a strike at Detroit's Fleetwood Plant, where bodies were made for GM's luxury vehicle, the Cadillac. Support strikes were also called in Oakland, California, Pontiac, Michigan and St. Louis, Missouri. Autoworkers around the nation engaged in action in support of the Flint sit-down strikers.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW : a memoir|last=Reuther |first= Victor G.|date=1978|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=9780395275153|edition=  UAW special |location=Boston|pages=150|oclc=26295254}}</ref>\n\nBack in Flint, the police tried to force the workers out of the plant in what became known as the \"Battle of Bulls Run.\" Over a hundred policemen attacked the pickets with tear gas and bullets, sending thirteen workers to the hospital with gunshot wounds. Victor manned the sound car and encouraged the workers to fight back, which they did by sling-shotting door hinges from the factory roof and turning fire hoses on the police in the 16-degree Fahrenheit winter night. Victor and Genora Johnson, a leader of the Women's Brigade, took turns in the sound car exhorting the workers to stand their ground.\n\nMichigan Governor, [[Frank Murphy]], called in 2,000 members of the National Guard, not to force the workers out of the plants, but to keep the peace. After a brilliant move, the workers were able to gain control of the only plant in the country that made [[Chevrolet]] engines. Finally, 44 days later, General Motors was forced to recognize the worker's right to unionize and signed its first collective bargaining agreement with the fledgling UAW.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW : a memoir|last=Reuther |first= Victor G.|date=1978|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=9780395275153|edition=  UAW special |location=Boston|oclc=26295254}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Flint sit-down strike|Flint Sit-Down Strike]] has become known as the Lexington and Valley Forge of American industrial unionism. Roy recalled, \"When the boys came out of the plants, I never saw a night like that and perhaps will never see it again. I liken it to a country experiencing independence, families reunited for the first time since the strike began, kids hanging onto daddy with tears of joy and happiness. It was a sea of humanity in which fears were no longer on the minds of the workers.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/51 51]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/51}}</ref>\n\nIn 1950, Reuther negotiated and signed with [[Charles Erwin Wilson|Charlie Wilson]], chief executive officer of General Motors, the [[Reuther's Treaty of Detroit|Treaty of Detroit]], an historic five-year labor contract that, in exchange for a commitment not to strike, gave rank-and-file workers better wages, health care, and pensions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/remembering-the-legacy-of-labor-day/2019/09/01/8c67cd08-cb2f-11e9-be05-f76ac4ec618c_story.html|title=Remembering the Legacy of Labor Day|last=Dionne Jr.|first=E.J.|date=September 2, 2019|website=Washington Post|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At the time, Fortune Magazine wrote that the Treaty of Detroit \u201cmade the worker to an amazing degree a middle class member of a middle class society.\u201d<ref>{{Cite book|title=America in Our Time: From World War II to Nixon--what Happened and why|last=Hodgson|first=Godfrey|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=1976|isbn=0691122881|location=|pages=82}}</ref>\n\n=== Chrysler ===\n[[Chrysler]] was next on the list of the young UAW. In March 1937, 60,000 Chrysler workers went on strike. When police started roughing up pickets and strikers, over 150,000 citizens gathered at Detroit's downtown Cadillac Square where Reuther and others led them in protest. After a four-week strike, Chrysler followed General Motors\u2019 lead and negotiated its first collective bargaining agreement with the UAW.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/52 52\u201353]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/52}}</ref>\n\n=== Ford Motor Company ===\n[[Henry Ford]] had stated that he would never allow his workers to unionize. His main enforcer was [[Harry Bennett]], who led a 3,000 man Security Department for Ford Motor Company, whose mandate was to intimidate, beat, and fire any worker who showed signs of favoring unionization. In 1932, when workers marched out of the giant [[Ford River Rouge Complex]] in protest to the speed-up of the assembly lines, they were attacked by Bennett's armed men and 5 workers were shot dead and hundreds suffered injuries.<ref>{{Cite book|title=LIFE AND TIMES OF WALTER REUTHER.|last=JAMES.|first=TENEYCK|date=2016|publisher=PAGE PUBLISHING, INC|isbn=9781683482086|location=[S.l.]|pages=212|oclc=975986306}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Labor-Strike-Ford Motor Company-Walter Reuther fifth from the left-Richard Frankensteen sixth from the left - NARA - 195593.tif|thumb|Battle of the Overpass, May 26, 1937, Walter Reuther fifth from left, Richard Frankensteen sixth from left]]\nBarely a month after the Chrysler signing, Reuther got permission from the [[Dearborn, Michigan|City of Dearborn]] to pass out handbills titled, \"Unionism, not Fordism\" on public property at Gate Four of the giant [[Ford River Rouge Complex]]. As he and three other UAW leaders climbed the stairs to the bridge, they were attacked by Bennett's \"enforcers\" who severely beat them.<ref>{{Cite book|title=LIFE AND TIMES OF WALTER REUTHER.|last=JAMES.|first=TENEYCK|date=2016|publisher=PAGE PUBLISHING, INC|isbn=9781683482086|location=[S.l.]|pages=214\u2013216|oclc=975986306}}</ref>\n\nReuther was instantly surrounded by at least a dozen men, knocked to the ground, kicked and punched in the head and body, picked up 4 feet parallel to the ground then slammed to the concrete repeatedly, then thrown and kicked down 3 flights of stairs. The pummeling continued as 4 or 5 men beat him in and out of parked cars, until a streetcar arrived with union women to pass out leaflets and the thugs turned their attention to viciously attack them.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/56 56]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/56}}</ref>\n\nPress photographers were attacked as well and their camera's confiscated but one camera was inconspicuously thrown into a convertible and the next day, the \"[[Battle of the Overpass]],\" was national news.\n\nThe beatings taken by the union organizers in the long run hurt Henry Ford more, as national sentiment turned against him. ''Time'' magazine published the photographs with descriptions of how the union men and women were mercilessly beaten by Henry Ford's paid thugs. Ford retaliated against ''Time'', ''Life'', and ''Fortune'' magazines by withdrawing all advertising.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Reuther|last=Frank.|first=Cormier|date=1970|publisher=Prentice-Hall|others=Eaton, William J.|isbn=9780137793143|location=Englewood Cliffs, N.J.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/103 103\u2013107]|oclc=91809|url=https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/103}}</ref>\n\nIt took four more years, but finally, in 1941, Henry Ford signed his first agreement with the UAW. Shortly after, Henry Ford told Walter Reuther: \"It was one of the most sensible things Harry Bennett ever did when he got the UAW into this plant.\" Reuther inquired, \"What do you mean?\" Ford replied, \"Well, you've been fighting General Motors and the Wall Street crowd. Now you're in here and we've given you a union shop and more than you got out of them. That puts you on our side, doesn't it? We can fight General Motors and Wall Street together, eh?\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/63 63]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/63}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1950s, Reuther and [[Henry Ford II]], CEO of Ford, toured a state-of-the-art engine plant in Cleveland. As they walked about the plant, Ford gestured to the cutting-edge, automated machines, saying, \"Walter, how are you going to get these robots to pay union dues?\" Without missing a beat, Reuther famously replied: \"Henry, how are you going to get them to buy your cars?\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2015/07/world-without-work/395294/|title=A World Without Work|last=Thompson|first=Derek|work=The Atlantic|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== \"500 Planes a Day\" ===\nIn 1940, in the midst of [[World War II]], the United States was producing fighter planes to help the allies in their war against [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler's]] aggression. The production was slow, inadequate, and threatening the security of the Allies. The US planned to construct new manufacturing plants specifically to produce more planes. That plan, however, would have taken two years to begin producing planes. The Allies did not have that time to spare. In response, Reuther proposed \"to transform the entire unused capacity of the auto industry into one huge plane production unit capable of turning out 500 Planes a Day.\" After getting the support of workers, he publicly announced the \"Reuther Plan: 500 Planes a Day,\" shortly before Christmas, 1940.<ref>{{Cite book|title=FDR, the war president, 1940\u20131943 : a history|last=1912\u20131999.|first=Davis, Kenneth S. (Kenneth Sydney)|date=2000|publisher=Random House|others=Rogers D. Spotswood Collection.|isbn=9780679415428|edition=1st|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/fdrwarpresident100davi/page/436 436]|oclc=43694290|url=https://archive.org/details/fdrwarpresident100davi/page/436}}</ref> He said, during a national radio address on December 28, 1940:\n\n<blockquote>In London they are huddled in the subways praying for aid from America. In America we are huddled over blueprints praying that Hitler will be obliging enough to postpone an \"all out\" attack on England for another two years until new plants finally begin to turn out engines and aircraft. We believe that without disturbing present aircraft plant production schedules we can supplement them by turning out 500 planes a day of a single standard fighting model by the use of idle automotive capacity. . . . England's battles, it used to be said, were won on the playing fields of Eton. America's can be won on the assembly lines of Detroit. Give England planes and there will be no need to give her men.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://reuther100.wayne.edu/pdf/500_Planes_Speech.pdf|title=More Airplanes for Defense|last=Reuther|first=Walter|date=|website=Walter P. Reuther Library|access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nA week after receiving the plan, on December 30, 1940, President Roosevelt wrote [[William S. Knudsen]], chairman of the [[War Production Board]], \"It is well worthwhile to give a good deal of attention to this (Reuther) program.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=FDR, the war president, 1940\u20131943 : a history|last=1912\u20131999.|first=Davis, Kenneth S. (Kenneth Sydney)|date=2000|publisher=Random House|others=Rogers D. Spotswood Collection.|isbn=9780679415428|edition=1st|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/fdrwarpresident100davi/page/437 437]|oclc=43694290|url=https://archive.org/details/fdrwarpresident100davi/page/437}}</ref> Three days later on January 2, 1941, Reuther met with President Roosevelt at the White House to discuss the possibility of implementing his plan for 500 Planes a Day.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/65 65]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/65}}</ref>\n\nGeneral Motors, Ford, and Chrysler all opposed the Reuther Plan because they wanted the government to build new plane and tank factories that could be sold to them at giveaway prices after the war.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/time-another-reuther-plan/|title=Time for Another Reuther Plan|last=Lichtenstein|first=Nelson|date=May 13, 2009|work=The Nation|access-date=March 3, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0027-8378}}</ref> They also disliked that labor had the audacity to stick their nose into production, which they felt was management's exclusive domain. [[Alfred P. Sloan]], chairman of General Motors, scoffed at the idea, stating, \"only about 10 to 15% of the machinery and equipment in an automobile factory can be utilized for the production of special defense material.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/66 66]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/66}}</ref>\n\nAfter the attack on [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|Pearl Harbor on December 7, 1941]], many of Reuther's proposals were implemented. Detroit's automobile plants produced planes and tanks in mass volume and became known as the center of the [[Arsenal of Democracy]], which gave the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] a decisive advantage to win the war. By 1943, Chrysler President, [[K. T. Keller]], reported that his company had converted 89% of its machine tools to wartime production, leading Washington Post publisher, [[Phil Graham]], to state that meant Reuther was 89% right.<ref>{{Cite book|title=LIFE AND TIMES OF WALTER REUTHER.|last=JAMES.|first=TENEYCK|date=2016|publisher=PAGE PUBLISHING, INC|isbn=9781683482086|location=[S.l.]|oclc=975986306}}</ref> At the war's end, ''Fortune'' magazine wrote: \"Reuther was right on track. Compared with many industrialists that sat back and hugged profits and the aimless agencies of Washington, the red-headed labor leader exhibited atomic spirit of action. He never let up.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/69 69]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/69}}</ref>\n\n=== Elected UAW president ===\nAfter the war ended in 1945, Reuther proved he would be a different type of labor leader when he led a strike challenging GM to increase workers wages by 30% without increasing the price of their new cars.&nbsp;Worker pay had been restricted during World War II and Reuther sought to get them a raise but not at the cost of increased inflation.&nbsp;Historically, when workers won a pay increase, the company would pass on the expense to their consumers.&nbsp;GM refused the pay increase and after a 113-day strike, the sides settled on an eighteen and a half cent hourly raise.&nbsp;Reuther's bold collective bargaining leadership in this strike catapulted him into the union's top position.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Reuther|last=Frank.|first=Cormier|date=1970|publisher=Prentice-Hall|others=Eaton, William J.|isbn=9780137793143|location=Englewood Cliffs, N.J.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/223 223\u2013230]|oclc=91809|url=https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/223}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 1946, Reuther won the election and became the president of the UAW in a very close race, defeating incumbent UAW president [[R. J. Thomas]] by a mere 124 votes, out of almost 9,000 cast. The new UAW president pledged his vision of \"a labor movement whose philosophy is to fight for the welfare of the public at large.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/81 81]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/81}}</ref> One of his first acts as president was to fight to integrate the American Bowling League, which had previously excluded black bowlers.&nbsp;He was a new kind of leader who viewed the labor movement as \"an instrument for social change.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/3 3]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/3}}</ref>\n\n==== Salary ====\nAlthough presidents of much smaller unions were making 3 or 4 times his salary, Reuther purposely kept his salary low to stay in touch, and show solidarity, with UAW members he represented. He never made an annual salary of more than $31,000. Author [[David Halberstam]] writes: \"His life was not about material things. The constant success of the union was reward enough.\"<ref name=\"Halberstam 1986 339\" />\n\n=== Expelling Communism from organized labor ===\nThe following 18 months after Reuther's election win, bitter battles erupted inside the UAW as Communist-backers of [[R. J. Thomas]] had a two-thirds majority on the UAW's Executive Board. One observer noted, \"The Commies threw everything but their hammer and sickle at Walter.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/85 85]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/85}}</ref> In November 1947, at the next UAW national convention, this time Reuther won the election overwhelmingly, severely weakening the Communist's hold on the union's leadership. ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine reported that Reuther's victory was \"the biggest setback of all time for the Communists in the American Labor Movement.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/86 86]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/86}}</ref>\n\nAs president, Reuther next sought to remove officers from Communist-dominated unions within the CIO, leading [[Hubert Humphrey]] to write,\"Communist infiltration of the CIO was a direct threat to the survival of all of our country's democratic institutions. The CIO's victory over the Communist party was a significant victory for our nation.\" In response, [[Trud (Russian newspaper)|Trud]], a Soviet newspaper, called Reuther a \"traitor and strikebreaker\" and a favorite of the [[United States Chamber of Commerce|U.S. Chamber of Commerce]]. The [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] called Reuther \"the most dangerous man in America and a Communist.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/86 86\u201387]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/86}}</ref> Despite removing Communists from the labor movement, [[J. Edgar Hoover]], Director of the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]], never stopped labeling Reuther a Communist for working in Russia and having early associations with Communists and Socialists. During World War II, J. Edgar Hoover considered subjecting Reuther, and his brothers Victor and Roy, to custodial detention.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/68 68]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/68}}</ref>\n\nIn 1959, at the request of the [[United States Department of State]], Reuther met with Soviet Premier [[Nikita Khrushchev]] to discuss, among other things, capitalism versus communism, organized labor, and US-Russia relations. The meeting happened in San Francisco at the [[Mark Hopkins Hotel]] and was front-page international news.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW : a memoir|last=Reuther |first= Victor G.|date=1978|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=9780395275153|edition=  UAW special |location=Boston|pages=395|oclc=26295254}}</ref> Later when Khrushchev met with President Kennedy at the [[Vienna summit|Vienna Summit]] in 1961, he told Kennedy, \"We hung the likes of Reuther in Russia in 1917.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW : a memoir|last=Reuther |first= Victor G.|date=1978|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=9780395275153|edition=  UAW special |location=Boston|pages=394\u201399|oclc=26295254}}</ref>\n\n=== Collective bargaining ===\nAs president of the UAW, Reuther negotiated contracts that included unprecedented standard-of-living increases for automobile workers. Such increases include annual raises based on productivity advances, cost-of-living increases, supplementary unemployment benefits, early-retirement options, and health and welfare benefits.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Walter-Reuther|title=Walter Reuther {{!}} American labour leader|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Photograph of President Truman in the Oval Office, conferring with labor leader Walter Reuther, president of the... - NARA - 200406.jpg|thumb|left|Walter Reuther (right) conferring with President Truman in the Oval Office, 1952]]\nHe employed a strategy called \"[[pattern bargaining]]\" against the [[Big Three (automobile manufacturers)|Big Three]] automobile manufacturers, [[General Motors]], [[Ford Motor Company]], and [[Chrysler]].<ref name=\"Alfred. 2009 149\">{{Cite book|title=The automobile and American life|last=Alfred.|first=Heitmann, John|date=2009|publisher=McFarland & Co|isbn=9780786440139|location=Jefferson, N.C.|pages=149|oclc=298304623}}</ref> He would first target a company that seemed most likely to accept his bargaining objective. If that target company refused offer concessions, Reuther would threaten a strike to halt production at its plants only while allowing production operations at its competitors' plants to go uninterrupted. As a result, the target company would accept Reuther's demands to prevent its competitors from absorbing its sales and market share. Once he secured the initial agreement, he would use it as a pattern against the other automobile companies, threatening to strike if they too did not match the same terms to which the initial target company agreed. Reuther employed pattern bargaining to leverage competition among automobile manufacturers, maximize the influence of labor, and reduce the frequency of costly strikes.<ref name=\"Alfred. 2009 149\"/>\n\nReuther tried to negotiate lower automobile prices for consumers with each contract, with limited success.<ref>Victor G. Reuther ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=zv2Nm7Ct17MC&q=The+Brothers+Reuther&dq=The+Brothers+Reuther&hl=en&sa=X&ei=7SvxTvTCOKLs0gHc-rGTAg&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAQ&safe=active The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW]'', p. 249</ref>\n\nAfter the [[bombing of Pearl Harbor]], Reuther strongly supported the war effort and refused to tolerate [[Wildcat strike action|wildcat strikes]] that might disrupt munitions production. He worked for the [[War Manpower Commission]], the Office of Production Management, and the [[War Production Board]].<ref>Arthur Herman, ''Freedom's Forge: How American Business Produced Victory in World War II,'' (2012) pp. 116\u201317, 196\u201397, 231.</ref> He led a [[United Auto Workers (UAW) strike of 1945-46|113-day strike]] against General Motors in 1945\u20131946; it only partially succeeded. He never received the power he wanted to inspect company books or have a say in management, but he achieved increasingly lucrative wage and benefits contracts.<ref>Michelle Brattain, \"Reuther, Walter Philip\"; ''American National Biography Online'' (2000)</ref>\n\nHe became president of the CIO in 1952, and negotiated a merger with [[George Meany]] and the American Federation of Labor immediately after, which took effect in 1955. In 1949 he led the CIO delegation to the London conference that set up the [[International Confederation of Free Trade Unions]] in opposition to the communist-dominated [[World Federation of Trade Unions]]. He had left the Socialist Party in 1939, and throughout the 1950s and 1960s was a leading spokesman for liberal interests in the CIO and in the Democratic Party.<ref name=\"Brattain 2000\">Brattain, \"Reuther, Walter Philip\"; ''American National Biography Online'' (2000)</ref>\n\n== Civil rights activism ==\n[[File:Photograph of White House Meeting with Civil Rights Leaders. June 22, 1963 - NARA - 194190 (no border).tif|thumb|Civil rights leaders with Vice President Johnson and Attorney General Robert Kennedy at the White House on June 22, 1963.]]Reuther was a strong supporter of the [[Civil Rights Movement]].<ref name=\":0\" /> He marched with King in [[Selma to Montgomery marches|Selma]],<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Birmingham campaign|Birmingham]],<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Selma to Montgomery marches|Montgomery]],<ref name=\":3\" /> and [[March Against Fear|Jackson]]<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> and when King and others were jailed in [[Birmingham campaign|Birmingham, Alabama]], and King authored his famous [[Letter from Birmingham Jail]], Reuther arranged $160,000 for the protestors' release.<ref name=\":6\" /> He also helped organize and finance the [[March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom|March on Washington]] on August 28, 1963, delivering remarks from the steps of the [[Lincoln Memorial]] shortly before King gave his historic \"[[I Have a Dream]]\" speech.<ref name=\":2\"/><ref name=\":8\" /> He served on the board of directors for the [[NAACP|National Association for the Advancement of Colored People]] (NAACP).<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nOn the 25th anniversary of the UAW, King wrote a letter to Reuther, congratulating him on his successes and observing:<blockquote>More than anyone else in America, you stand out as the shining symbol of democratic trade unionism. Through trials, efforts and your unswerving devotion to humanitarian causes, you have made life more meaningful for millions of working people. Through moments of difficulty and strong obstacles, you have stood firm for what you believe, knowing that in the long run 'Truth crushed to earth will rise again.' As I have heard you say, the true measure of a man is where he stands in moments of challenge and controversy, when the only consolation he gains is the quiet whisper of an inner voice saying there are things so eternally true and significant that they are worth dying for, if necessary. You have demonstrated over the years that you can stand up in moments of challenge and controversy. One day all of America will be proud of your achievements, and will record your work as one of the glowing epics of our heritage.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the World Together: My Father Walter Reuther, The Liberal Warrior|last=Reuther|first=Elisabeth|publisher=Living Force Publishing|year=2004|isbn=0975379216|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/190 190]|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/190}}</ref></blockquote>[[File:1963 march on washington.jpg|thumb|Leaders of the March on Washington]]\n\n[[Coretta Scott King]] later said, <blockquote>Walter Reuther was to black people, the most widely known and respected white labor leader in the nation. He was there when the storm clouds were thick.  We remember him in Montgomery. He was in Birmingham. He marched with us in Selma, and Jackson, Mississippi and in Washington.&nbsp;... Only yesterday, there he was again in Charleston, South Carolina, the leader of a million and a half workers giving personal support to a strike of only 400 black women.&nbsp;...  He was a big man, so of course he had enemies and detractors. He had the courage to be with the minority when it was right.  He was a simple man in his personal life, a rare quality in these flamboyant times&nbsp;... but if his ways were simple, his ideas were grand.  He aroused the imagination of millions.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/350 350\u201351]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/350}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn the early 1930s, Reuther first challenged racism as a student at what is now Wayne State University. When a local hotel, which had agreed with the college to let students use its swimming pool, refused to let blacks swim, he organized a picket line. The protest surrounded the block. As a result, the hotel closed its pool to all students.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Walter Reuther|last=1943\u2013|first=Carew, Anthony|date=1993|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=9780719021886|location=Manchester|pages=264|oclc=27676666}}</ref> In a 2013 interview with ''The New York Times'', President [[Barack Obama]] said, <blockquote>\"When you think about the coalition that brought about civil rights, it wasn\u2019t just folks who believed in racial equality; it was people who believed in working folks having a fair shot. It was Walter Reuther and the UAW coming down here because they understood that if there are some workers who are not getting a fair deal then ultimately that\u2019s going to undercut their ability to get a fair deal.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/28/us/politics/interview-with-president-obama.html|title=Interview with President Obama|last=|first=|date=July 27, 2013|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Walk to Freedom, June 23, 1963 ===\nThe [[Detroit Walk to Freedom|Walk to Freedom]] was a mass march during the [[Civil Rights Movement]] on June 23, 1963 in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]]. The purpose of the demonstration was to protest racism, segregation, and the brutality inflicted upon civil rights activists in the South as well as the discrimination facing African-Americans in the North such as inequality in hiring, wages, education, and housing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reuther.wayne.edu/node/7858|title=Walter P. Reuther Library|website=reuther.wayne.edu|language=en|access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref> In some ways, it was considered a dress rehearsal for the [[March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom]], which was scheduled for two months later.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Sweet land of liberty : the forgotten struggle for civil rights in the North|last=1962\u2013|first=Sugrue, Thomas J.|year=2008|isbn=9780679643036|edition=First|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/sweetlandofliber00sugr/page/298 298\u2013301]|oclc=191732290|url=https://archive.org/details/sweetlandofliber00sugr/page/298}}</ref> An estimated 125,000 people attended and it was the largest civil rights demonstration in the nation's history up to that date.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/local/michigan-history/2017/09/02/walter-reuther-uaw-giant/105249350/|title=Walter Reuther was labor legend on a global scale|work=Detroit News|access-date=March 18, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\nReuther mobilized support for the protest and donated office space at the UAW's headquarters Solidarity House for Martin Luther King, Jr. to organize the event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uawregion8.net/Activist-HOF/WReuther.htm|title=Region 8|website=www.uawregion8.net|access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref> Along with others, including King, Reuther marched down [[Woodward Avenue]] and delivered remarks afterwards at [[Cobo Center|Cobo Hall]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/detroits-forgotten-dream/2013/06/20/4ca4b61a-d868-11e2-a9f2-42ee3912ae0e_story.html|title=Detroit's forgotten 'Dream'|last=Maraniss|first=David|date=June 20, 2013|work=Washington Post|access-date=March 18, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> It was there that King delivered his first version of his \"I Have a Dream,\" speech, having penned it, at least partially, inside his office at Solidarity House.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://detroitnaacp.org/50th-anniversary-freedom-walk-detroit-press-conference/|title=50th Anniversary Freedom Walk Detroit Press Conference|last=|first=|date=June 10, 2013|website=Detroit NAACP|access-date=March 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.peoplesworld.org/article/detroit-remembers-50-years-after-king-s-i-have-a-dream-speech/|title=Detroit remembers 50 years after King's \"I Have a Dream\" speech|last=Rummel|first=John|date=June 11, 2013|website=Peoples World|access-date=March 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{external media | width = 210px | float = right | audio1 = [http://openvault.wgbh.org/collections/march_on_washington/ern-coverage Complete radio coverage of the March on Washington], August 28, 1963, Educational Radio Network<ref name=\"ern\">{{cite web | title =Special Collections, March on Washington, Parts 1\u201317 | work = Open Vault | publisher = at [[WGBH Educational Foundation|WGBH]] | date = August 28, 1963 | url =http://openvault.wgbh.org/collections/march_on_washington/ern-coverage |access-date= March 19, 2018 }}</ref>\n| audio2 = [http://openvault.wgbh.org/catalog/A_CB387942466C46F6BAE6528BAFD53055#at_2417.423_s Walter Reuther's remarks begin at 40:40], August 28, 1963, Educational Radio Network<ref name=\"ern2\">{{cite web | title =Special Collections, March on Washington, Part 17 | work = Open Vault | publisher = at [[WGBH Educational Foundation|WGBH]] | date = August 28, 1963 | url = http://openvault.wgbh.org/catalog/A_CB387942466C46F6BAE6528BAFD53055#at_2417.423_s | access-date= March 19, 2018 }}</ref>\n }}\n\n=== March on Washington, August 28, 1963 ===\n[[File:March-on-washington-jobs-freedom-program.jpg|thumb|Official program of March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom|271x271px]]The [[March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom]] was held in [[Washington, D.C.]] on Wednesday, August 28, 1963. The protest sought to advocate for the civil and economic rights of [[African American]]s. Along with the [[Big Six (activists)|Big Six]] and three white religious leaders, Reuther helped organize the march.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://kingencyclopedia.stanford.edu/encyclopedia/encyclopedia/enc_reuther_walter_philip_1907_1970/|title=Reuther, Walter Philip (1907\u20131970)|website=kingencyclopedia.stanford.edu|access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":8\" />  Originally, the march was planned to take place outside of the [[United States Capitol|Capitol Building]]. Reuther, however, persuaded the other organizers to move the march to the [[Lincoln Memorial]]. He believed the Lincoln Memorial would be less threatening to Congress and the occasion would be more appropriate underneath the gaze of Abraham Lincoln's statute. The committee, notably Rustin, agreed to move the site on the condition that Reuther pay for a $19,000 sound system so that everyone on the [[National Mall]] could hear the speakers and musicians.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Once in a great city : a Detroit story|last=David.|first=Maraniss|year=|isbn=9781476748399|edition=First Simon & Schuster hardcover|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/onceingreatcityd00mara/page/236 236]|oclc=894936463|url=https://archive.org/details/onceingreatcityd00mara/page/236}}</ref> \nReuther and the UAW financed bus transportation for 5,000 of its rank-and-file members, providing the largest single contingent from any organization.<ref>{{Cite book|title=American vanguard : the United Auto Workers during the Reuther years, 1935-1970|last=1932-|first=Barnard, John|date=2004|publisher=Wayne State University Press|isbn=9780814332979|location=Detroit|pages=388|oclc=52819692}}</ref> The UAW also paid for and brought thousands of signs for marchers to carry. Among other things, the signs read: \"There Is No Halfway House on the Road to Freedom,\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.colorlines.com/articles/1963-march-washington-photos|title=The 1963 March on Washington in Photos|last=cl_admin|date=August 23, 2013|work=Colorlines|access-date=March 21, 2018|language=en}}</ref> \"Equal Rights and Jobs NOW,\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/114408/march-washington-50th-anniversary-walter-reuthers-speech|title=The White Man Whose 'March on Washington' Speech You Should Remember Too|work=The New Republic|access-date=March 21, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> \"UAW Supports Freedom March,\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://americanhistory.si.edu/changing-america-emancipation-proclamation-1863-and-march-washington-1963/1963/march-washington|title=March on Washington|website=National Museum of American History|language=en|access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref> \"in Freedom we are Born, in Freedom we must Live,\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.com/melissa-harris-perry/how-womens-voices-were-excluded-the|title=How women's voices were excluded from the March|work=MSNBC|access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref> and \"Before we'll be a Slave, we'll be Buried in our Grave.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/EJ1021080.pdf|title=The Move to Unity, labor's role in the March on Washington|last=Jones|first=William|date=|website=|access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nReuther was the most prominent white organizer scheduled to speak. In his remarks, on the steps of the [[Lincoln Memorial]], he urged Americans to pressure their politicians to act to address racial injustices. He said:\n[[File:President John F. Kennedy and Vice President Lyndon B. Johnson Meet with Organizers of \"March on Washington\".jpg|thumb|[[John F. Kennedy|Kennedy]] and [[Lyndon B. Johnson|Johnson]] with organizers of the \"March on Washington\" at the White House on August 28, 1963 ]]\n\n<blockquote>American democracy is on trial in the eyes of the world\u2026 We cannot successfully preach democracy in the world unless we first practice democracy at home. American democracy will lack the moral credentials and be both unequal to and unworthy of leading the forces of freedom against the forces of tyranny unless we take bold, affirmative, adequate steps to bridge the moral gap between American democracy's noble promises and its ugly practices in the field of civil rights.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://billmoyers.com/content/meet-the-march-organizers/9/|title=Meet the 1963 March on Washington Organizers {{!}} BillMoyers.com|work=BillMoyers.com|access-date=2018-03-21|language=en-US}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nAccording to [[Irving Bluestone]], who was standing near the platform while Reuther delivered his remarks, he overheard two black women talking. One asked, \"Who is that white man?\" The other replied, \"Don't you know him? That's the white Martin Luther King.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jones|first=William|date=Fall 2013|title=The Move to Unity, Labor's Role in the March on Washington|url=https://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/EJ1021080.pdf|journal=American Educator|volume=|pages=35|via=}}</ref> After the march, the civil rights leaders met with President Kennedy at the White House to discuss civil rights legislation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jfklibrary.org/Asset-Viewer/lCuiXLZD20Go3B0o7rpWvg.aspx|title=President Kennedy with leaders of the March on Washington - John F. Kennedy Presidential Library & Museum|website=www.jfklibrary.org|access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Cesar Chavez and the United Farm Workers ===\nIn December 1965, Reuther visited [[Cesar Chavez]] and the striking grape growers in [[Delano, California|Delano]], [[California]]. Two months earlier, Reuther's brother and colleague, Roy, had visited the striking farmworkers. Upon returning from his visit, Roy urged Walter to support Chavez.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Cesar Chavez : autobiography of La Causa|last=E.|first=Levy, Jacques|date=2007|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|others=Chavez, Cesar, 1927-1993., Ross, Fred, Jr., Levy, Jacqueline M.|isbn=9780816650491|edition=  1st University of Minnesota Press |location=Minneapolis|pages=202|oclc=227339180}}</ref> At that time, Chavez's struggle for workers' rights was little known to the American public, but Reuther's visit garnered national media attention, making it difficult for the growers to ignore the striking grape pickers. During the trip, Reuther marched with Chavez and his fellow strikers, carrying picket signs reading \"Huelga.\" Reuther also spoke to packed union hall, declaring, \"This is not your strike, this is our strike!\" He pledged that the UAW would provide $7,500 per month to the [[United Farm Workers]]' strike fund for the duration of the strike.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Cesar Chavez|last=Hal.|first=Marcovitz|date=2003|publisher=Chelsea House Publishers|isbn=9780791072530|location=Philadelphia|pages=53\u201354|oclc=50913476}}</ref>\n\nUpon returning to Detroit, Reuther contacted Senator [[Robert F. Kennedy]], who was on the [[United States Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor and Pensions|Senate Labor Committee]], requesting that Kennedy visit Chavez in Delano to learn about and support the farmworkers. Kennedy obliged, ultimately becoming the most visible supporter of the farmworkers' movement.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The 100 greatest Americans of the 20th century : a social justice hall of fame|last=1948-|first=Dreier, Peter|date=2012|publisher=Nation Books|isbn=9781568586816|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/235 235, 339]|oclc=701015405|url=https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/235}}</ref> Reuther visited Chavez many times, including once during Chavez's hunger strike. During that visit, Reuther made a $50,000 donation to Chavez's struggle to which Chavez said, \"Walter, you have given me great confidence.\" Reuther replied, \"You will prevail for your cause is just.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/287 287\u201388]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/287}}</ref> In honor of the Reuther brothers' early and sustained support, the United Farm Workers named a building at their Delano headquarters the \"Roy Reuther Administration Building.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/ca3945/|title=Forty Acres, Roy Reuther Administration Building, 30168 Garces Highway (Northwest Corner of Garces Highway and Mettler Avenue), Delano, Kern County, CA|work=The Library of Congress|access-date=March 22, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Assassination attempts ==\nIn 1938, gunmen barged into Reuther's apartment in an attempt to kidnap and murder the labor leader. The criminals were thwarted by a small group of Reuther friends and relatives. Nobody was injured.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://reuther100.wayne.edu/bio.php?pg=3|title=Walter P. Reuther|website=reuther100.wayne.edu|access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Eleanor Roosevelt, Bessie Hillman, Jacob Potofsky, and Walter Reuther in New York City - NARA - 195505.jpg|thumb|Eleanor Roosevelt, Bessie Hillman, Jacob Potofsky, and Walter Reuther in New York City, January 7, 1957.|left]]On April 20, 1948, Reuther barely survived a double-barrel shotgun blast that ripped through his kitchen window as he was preparing a late evening snack. As the gunshot went off at 9:48&nbsp;p.m. E.S.T.,<ref name=\"United Press 1948, page 2\">United Press, \u201cReuther Shot in Detroit Home - Auto Union Official Victim of Ambush,\u201d ''The San Bernardino Daily Sun'', San Bernardino, California, Wednesday April 21, 1948, Volume LIV, Number 201, page 2.</ref> Reuther happened to turn toward his wife, and was hit in his right arm instead of the chest and heart.<ref>Pietrusza, David, 1948: Harry Truman's Improbable Victory and the Year That Transformed America, Union Square Press, 2011, p. 153</ref> Four slugs of the type used to kill large game had shattered his right arm into 150 pieces of bone. Another slug pierced his back and exited out his stomach. The assailant \u201cfled in a bright red four-door Ford sedan, police said.\u201d<ref>United Press, \u201cUnknown Assailant Wounds Reuther, Auto Union Head - Labor Leader Hit in Arm, Shoulder  by Shotgun Blast Through Kitchen Window,\u201d ''The San Bernardino Daily Sun'', San Bernardino, California, Wednesday April 21, 1948, Volume LIV, Number 201, page 1.</ref> Reuther, who did not lose consciousness, cursed his attacker as he was initially being treated by his next-door-neighbor, a doctor, as he lay on the kitchen floor. \u201c\u2018Those dirty sons of bitches!\u2019 Reuther cried. \u2018They have to shoot a man in the back. They won\u2019t come out in the open and fight.\u2019\u201d<ref name=\"United Press 1948, page 2\"/>  As doctors fought to save his life, he became infected with malaria and hepatitis from blood transfusions. Through months of therapy, he regained partial use of his right arm, but for the rest of his life had to train himself to write and shake with his left hand.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Reuther|last=Frank|first=Cormier|date=1970|publisher=Prentice-Hall|others=Eaton, William J|isbn=9780137793143|location=Englewood Cliffs, N.J|pages=[https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/155 155\u201356]|oclc=91809|url=https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/155}}</ref> When Attorney General, [[Tom C. Clark|Tom Clark]], requested [[J. Edgar Hoover]] to get the FBI to investigate the shooting, Hoover refused, stating, \"I'm not going to send in the FBI every time some nigger woman gets raped.\"<ref name=\"Raskin\"/><ref>{{Cite book|title=The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW : a memoir|last=Reuther |first= Victor G.|date=1978|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=9780395275153|edition=  UAW special |location=Boston|pages=281|oclc=26295254}}</ref> The shooting was never solved.\nThirteen months after the attack, Reuther's brother Victor was almost killed by a similar shooting from a double-barrel shotgun. The blast traveled through his living room window and hit him in the face, throat, and chest. Victor's right eye had been shot out and had to be removed.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW : a memoir|last=Reuther |first= Victor G.|date=1978|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=9780395275153|edition=  UAW special |location=Boston|pages=484\u201386|oclc=26295254}}</ref> Victor said, \"The attack on me was a way of serving notice to Walter. 'We didn't get you yet, but we're still around.'\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/10 10]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/10}}</ref> The shooting of Victor was also never solved.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/11 11\u201313]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/06/05/us/victor-reuther-influential-labor-leader-dies-at-92.html|title=Victor Reuther, Influential Labor Leader, Dies at 92|last=Saxon|first=Wolfgang|date=June 5, 2004|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 18, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of both shootings, [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] wrote: \"It seems unthinkable that the police have never been able to discover who shot Walter Reuther and because of that, in all probability, the same person perhaps has felt he could get away with shooting another brother. . . . [W]e have a right to protect men who are working in the interests of their fellow men.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=She was one of us : Eleanor Roosevelt and the American worker|last=Brigid.|first=O'Farrell|date=2010|publisher=ILR Press|isbn=9780801448805|location=Ithaca, N.Y.|pages=144|oclc=732957167}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nOn May 9, 1970, Walter Reuther, his wife May, architect [[Oscar Stonorov]], Reuther's bodyguard William Wolfman, the pilot and co-pilot were killed when their chartered [[Learjet 23]] crashed in flames at 9:33&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Time]]. The plane, arriving from Detroit in rain and fog, was on final approach to [[Pellston Regional Airport]] in [[Pellston, Michigan|Pellston]], Michigan, near the UAW's recreational and educational facility at [[Black Lake (Michigan)|Black Lake, Michigan]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/0901.html |title=Reuther Dies in Jet Crash With Wife and 4 Others |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=May 11, 1970 |accessdate=October 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.planecrashinfo.com/famous1970s.htm planecrashinfo.com Famous People Who Died in Aviation Accidents: 1970s]</ref> The [[National Transportation Safety Board]] discovered that the plane's [[altimeter]] was missing parts, some incorrect parts were installed, and one of its parts had been installed upside down,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1971/02/19/page/21/article/tie-faulty-altimeter-to-reuthers-death |title=Tie Faulty Altimeter to Reuther's Death  |date=February 19, 1971 |website=archives.chicagotribune.com |publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]] |access-date=July 11, 2016}}</ref> leading some to speculate that Reuther may have been murdered.<ref>See Michael Parenti, \"The Wonderful Life and Strange Death of Walter Reuther,\" Dirty Truths (City Lights Books, 1996), page 201.</ref> Reuther had been subjected earlier to two attempted assassinations.\n\n== Personal life ==\nWalter and May Reuther were married on March 13, 1936, after meeting on a streetcar in Detroit only six weeks earlier.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the World Together: My Father Walter Reuther, the Liberal Warrior|last=Dickmeyer, Reuther|first=Elisabeth|publisher=Living Force|year=2004|isbn=9780975379219|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/36 36-37]|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/36}}</ref> They had two daughters, Linda born in 1942 and Elisabeth in 1947.\n\nReuther led a simple, austere lifestyle. He neither smoked nor drank alcohol because he felt it sapped a person's vitality. For his daily lunch in his office he had the same menu: a sandwich and a cup of tea. He was an early riser. Author [[William Manchester]] wrote that Reuther's associates saw him as a \u201ctrue [[Asceticism|ascetic]].\u201d<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the World Together: My Father Walter Reuther, the Liberal Warrior|last=Dickmeyer, Reuther|first=Elisabeth|publisher=Living Force Publishing|year=2004|isbn=9780975379219|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/141 141]|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/141}}</ref>\n\nTo relax he liked to hike, fish and play tennis. His favorite music was German Lieder, Classical, Negro Spirituals and Union Songs. Although sometimes perceived as rigid with no sense of humor, Walter\u2019s colleague and friend [[Irving Bluestone]] said: \u201cThat wasn't true at all. He was a very easy person to work with and be with. He had a good sense of humor and could laugh at himself. And occasionally, when he was excited enough, he would use profanity just like anyone else coming out of the shop.\u201d<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the World Together: My Father Walter Reuther, the Liberal Warrior|last=Dickmeyer, Reuther|first=Elisabeth|publisher=Living Force|year=2004|isbn=9780975379219|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/340 340]|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/340}}</ref>\n\nReuther enjoyed being and working outdoors in nature. Whether building a fish ladder for the trout underneath their bridge or planting a [[Japanese garden|Japanese Garden]] for May that she could view outside their bedroom window, he enjoyed and relaxed by working on outdoor projects on his Paint Creek property, located outside [[Rochester, Michigan]]. He and his daughter Lisa planted an [[arboretum]], including over 50 types of tree, at their Paint Creek home. He was an expert woodworker and built much of the furniture for their home with his own hands. After the assassination attempt in 1948, which shattered his arm in 150 pieces, he rehabilitated his arm by squeezing a hard rubber ball and pushing out the walls to build their Paint Creek home from what had been a one-room cottage. He remarked, \u201cI got a good house and a good hand, all for the same money.\u201d<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the World Together: My Father Walter Reuther, the Liberal Warrior|last=Dickmeyer, Reuther|first=Elisabeth|publisher=Living Force Publishing|year=2004|isbn=9780975379219|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/115 115-117]|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/115}}</ref>\n\nMay was Walter's sounding board and close advisor throughout his public life. May was a teacher and involved in organizing a teachers\u2019 union. Early on she was making $60 a week of which she gave most to help organize auto workers into the fledgling UAW. She soon gave up her teaching career to become Walter's full-time secretary, earning $15 per week. She was active in many charities and programs to uplift the community.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Brothers Reuther and the Story of the UAW|last=Reuther|first=Victor G.|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|year=1978|isbn=9780395275153|location=|pages=127}}</ref> May marched side-by-side with Walter in the civil rights struggles in Selma and elsewhere. She hosted [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] at their Paint Creek home.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the World Together: My Father Walter Reuther, the Liberal Warrior|last=Reuther Dickmeyer|first=Elisabeth|publisher=Living Force|year=2004|isbn=9780975379219|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/195 195]|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/195}}</ref> She also served as president of the PTA at their daughter's school.<ref name=\":3\" /> After the assassination attempt on Walter's life in 1948, May decided to spend most of her time at home trying to give their two daughters as normal a life as possible; although, the family had bodyguards and attack dogs living with them the rest of their lives.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Honors and awards ==\n[[File:ABOUT-ReutherTall-600.jpg|thumb|Walter Reuther statue located at the Walter and May Reuther UAW Family Education Center in Black Lake, Michigan.]]\n\n* President [[Bill Clinton]] awarded Reuther the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] posthumously in 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=50577|title=William J. Clinton: Remarks on Presenting the Presidential Medal of Freedom|website=www.presidency.ucsb.edu|access-date=February 28, 2018}}</ref>\n* Walter Reuther appears in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine's list of the 100 most influential people of the 20th century.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,26473,00.html|title=TIME 100 Persons of The Century|date=June 6, 1999|work=Time|access-date=February 28, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0040-781X}}</ref>\n* Reuther was inducted into the [[United States Department of Labor|Department of Labor's]] Hall of Honor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dol.gov/general/aboutdol/hallofhonor/1990_reuther|title=Hall of Honor Inductee: Walter P. Reuther|date=December 9, 2015|work=United States Department of Labor|access-date=March 20, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n* Reuther received the [[Eugene V. Debs Award]] in 1968 for his work in Industrial Unionism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://debsfoundation.org/index.php/landing/eugene-v-debs-award/|title=Eugene V. Debs Award|last= |date=September 18, 2017|website=Eugene V. Debs Foundation Website|publisher=Eugene V. Debs Foundation}}</ref>\n* The National Committee for Israel Labor gave Reuther the Histadrut Humanitarian Award in 1958.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jta.org/1958/06/18/archive/president-of-united-automobile-workers-union-gets-histadrut-award|title=President of United Automobile Workers Union Gets Histadrut Award {{!}} Jewish Telegraphic Agency|website=www.jta.org|language=en-US|access-date=March 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* The [[Weizmann Institute of Science]] in 1968 gave Reuther the Weizmann Award in the Sciences and Humanities<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wis-wander.weizmann.ac.il/weizmann-award-sciences-and-humanities|title=Weizmann Award in the Sciences and Humanities \u2013 News, Features and Discoveries from the Weizmann Institute of Science|date=November 1, 1999|work=Weizmann Wonder Wander|access-date=February 28, 2018|language=en}}</ref> and established the Walter P. Reuther Chair of Research in the Peaceful Uses of Atomic Energy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weizmann.ac.il/acadaff/Scientific_Activities/2007/Chairs.html|title=Scientific Activities: Weizmann Professorial Chairs, CDC's and Fellowships|website=www.weizmann.ac.il|access-date=February 28, 2018}}</ref>\n* Reuther received honorary degrees from, among other institutions, [[Harvard University]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oasis.lib.harvard.edu/oasis/primo?id=hua04003#container_3_25|title=Honorary Degree Recipients, June 12, 1969|last=|first=|date=|website=Harvard University|access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> [[University of Michigan]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://president.umich.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2014/06/Honorary-Degrees-1836-Present-1.pdf|title=Honorary Degrees Awarded 1836\u2013Present|last=|first=|date=|website=University of Michigan|access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> [[Oakland University]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oakland.edu/Assets/Oakland/provost/files-and-documents/Honorary-Degree/Honorary%20Degree%20Recipients_1963%20to%20Spring%202016.pdf|title=Honorary Degree Recipients 1963\u2013Present|last=|first=|date=|website=Oakland University|access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> [[Tuskegee University]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/59632339/|title=The Lincoln Star from Lincoln, Nebraska on June 1, 1965 \u00b7 Page 24|work=Newspapers.com|access-date=March 24, 2018|language=en}}</ref> and [[University of Rhode Island]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.uri.edu/commencement/honorary-degree-recipients/|title=Honorary Degree Recipients|website=web.uri.edu|language=en-US|access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref>\n* The Reuther-Chavez Award was created in 2002 by [[Americans for Democratic Action]] \"to recognize important activist, scholarly and journalistic contributions on behalf of workers' rights, especially the right to unionize and bargain collectively.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digitalcommons.ilr.cornell.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1378&context=articles|title=Labor's New Opening to International Human Rights Standards|last=Compa|first=Lance|date=|website=Digital Commons|access-date=March 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* The Walter P. Reuther Humanitarian Award was created in 1999 by [[Wayne State University]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wayne.edu/newsroom/release/1999/11/30/civil-rights-leader-lowery-to-receive-reuther-award-from-wayne-state-university-1317|title=Civil rights leader Lowery to receive Reuther Award from Wayne State University \u2013 Newsroom \u2013 Wayne State University|last=University|first=Wayne State|access-date=March 5, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n* There are three portraits and one sculpture of Reuther in the collection of the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian Institute's]] [[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://npg.si.edu/portraits/search|title=Portrait Search|language=en|access-date=March 20, 2018}}</ref>\n* Reuther appeared on the covers of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' Magazine twice, ''[[Newsweek]]'' three times, and ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine once.\n\n== Walter P. Reuther Humanitarian Award ==\n[[File:Reuther South.jpg|thumb|Walter P. Reuther Library, Wayne State University, Detroit, Michigan]]\nIn 1999, [[Wayne State University]], in collaboration with the UAW and the Reuther family, created the Walter P. Reuther Humanitarian Award to honor individuals who embody the spirit, vision, and values of Reuther.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://today.wayne.edu/news/1999/11/30/civil-rights-leader-lowery-to-receive-reuther-award-from-wayne-state-university-1317|title=Civil rights leader Lowery to receive Reuther Award from Wayne State University \u2013 Newsroom \u2013 Wayne State University|last=University|first=Wayne State|date=November 30, 1999|work=|access-date=October 27, 2019}}</ref> To date, the recipients of the award include civil rights activist [[Rosa Parks]], Congressman [[John Dingell]], civil rights activist [[Joseph Lowery]], UAW president [[Douglas Fraser]], and civil rights activist and Congressman [[John Lewis (civil rights leader)|John Lewis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://today.wayne.edu/news/2020/02/05/wayne-state-uaw-honor-civil-rights-legend-rep-john-lewis-35309|title=Wayne State, UAW honor civil rights legend Rep. John Lewis|last=|first=|date=February 5, 2020|website=Wayne State University|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Monuments ==\n[[File:I-696.svg|thumb|upright|Walter P. Reuther Freeway]]\n* [[Walter P. Reuther Library|Walter P. Reuther Library of Labor and Urban Affairs]], the largest labor archives in North America, located on the campus of [[Wayne State University]] in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]]\n* Walter Reuther Statue at Heritage Port, [[Wheeling, West Virginia]]. In Reuther's hometown, the seven foot statue is displayed outside the Convention Center alongside the [[Ohio River]] \n* [[Walter P. Reuther Freeway]] (I-696), stretching from the eastern to western suburbs of Detroit\n* Walter and May Reuther Family Education Center, [[Black Lake (Michigan)|Black Lake, Michigan]]\n* Walter Reuther Psychiatric Hospital, [[Westland, Michigan]]\n* Reuther Middle School, [[Rochester, Michigan]]\n* [[Walter Reuther Central High School]], [[Kenosha, Wisconsin]]\n\n== Archival records ==\nThe archival records of Reuther can be found mostly at the [[Walter P. Reuther Library|Walter P. Reuther Library of Labor and Urban Affairs]]. Notable are the ''UAW President's Office: Walter P. Reuther Records,'' an extensive collection that documents his time as President with the UAW. The materials include Reuther's personal correspondence, writings, photographs, official memorandum, and other various record types. Researchers are encouraged to contact the Reuther library for inquiries or access to materials. A guide to Reuther's archival materials can be found [http://reuther.wayne.edu/files/LR000261.pdf here].\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Biography|Organized labour}}\n*[[UAW|United Automobile Workers]]\n*[[AFL\u2013CIO|American Federation of Labor-Congress of Industrial Organizations]]\n*[[Americans for Democratic Action]]\n*[[Walter P. Reuther Library]]\n*[[List of civil rights leaders]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n'''Secondary sources:'''\n* Barnard, John. ''American Vanguard: The United Auto Workers during the Reuther Years, 1935\u20131970.'' Wayne State U. Press, 2004. 607 pp.\n* Boyle, Kevin. ''The UAW and the Heyday of American Liberalism, 1945\u20131968'' (1995)\n* Brattain, Michelle. \"Reuther, Walter Philip\"; [http://www.anb.org/articles/15/15-00570.html ''American National Biography Online'' Feb. 2000] Access March 21, 2015\n* Carew, Anthony. ''Walter Reuther'' (1993)\n* [[Kempton, Murray]]. \"The Reuther Brothers\" in ''Part of Our Time: Some Ruins and Monuments of the Thirties'' (1955, repr. 1998, repr. 2004)\n* Kornhauser, Arthur et al. ''When Labor Votes: A Study of Auto Workers'' (1956)\n* Goode, Bill. ''Infighting in the UAW: The 1946 Election and the Ascendancy of Walter Reuther'' (1994)\n* Parenti, Michael and Peggy Norton. ''The Wonderful Life and Strange Death of Walter Reuther'' (1996)\n* Zieger, Robert H. ''The CIO, 1935\u20131955'' (1995)\n* Reuther, Sasha, ''[[imdbtitle:1344811|Brothers on the Line]]'', Documentary (2012)\n\n'''Primary sources:'''\n*The [[Walter P. Reuther Library]], Archives of Labor and Urban Affairs on the campus of [[Wayne State University]] contains numerous collections related to Walter Reuther, most notably the [https://reuther.wayne.edu/node/2984 UAW President's Office: Walter P. Reuther Files], which \"reflect all phases of his career as president, UAW West Side Local 174 (1936); UAW Executive Board member (1936); director, UAW General Motors Department (1939\u201348); UAW vice-president (1942\u201346); UAW president (1946\u201370); president, ClO (1952\u201355); vice-president, AFL-CIO (1955\u201367); and president, AFL-CIO Industrial Union Department (1955\u201367).\"\n*Christman, Henry M. ed. ''Walter P. Reuther: Selected Papers'' (1961)\n*Reuther, Victor \"The Brothers Reuther and The Story of the UAW: A Memoir\" (1976)\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/0901.html Obituary], ''New York Times'', May 11, 1970\n* [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,989782,00.html ''Time Magazine'', Walter Reuther: Working-Class Hero]\n* {{Find a Grave|2262}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090325034818/http://www.airdisaster.com/reports/ntsb/AAR71-03.pdf NTSB Accident Report Number: NTSB-AAR-71-3]\n*[http://www.hrc.utexas.edu/multimedia/video/2008/wallace/reuther_walter.html Walter Reuther] interviewed by [[Mike Wallace]] on ''The Mike Wallace Interview'' January 25, 1958\n* [http://reuther100.wayne.edu/ The Reuther 100] Web site was established with IMLS grant money to commemorate the life of Walter P. Reuther on what would have been his 100th birthday.\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box|\n before= [[R. J. Thomas]] |\n title= President, [[United Auto Workers]] |\n years= 1946\u20131970 |\n after= [[Leonard Woodcock]]\n}}\n{{Succession box|\n  before= [[Philip Murray]]|\n  title= President, [[Congress of Industrial Organizations]] |\n  years= 1952\u20131955 |\n  after= Office abolished<br>(The merged AFL-CIO was led by [[George Meany]].)\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reuther, Walter}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:Leaders of American trade unions]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Congress of Industrial Organizations people]]\n[[Category:Fordson High School alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Wheeling, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:United Automobile Workers people]]\n[[Category:American socialists]]\n[[Category:Michigan Democrats]]\n[[Category:Victims of aviation accidents or incidents in the United States]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:Trade unionists from West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Trade unionists from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Activists from Detroit]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{short description|Labor union leader}}\n{{lead too long|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = Walter Reuther Department of Labor Hall of Honor.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Portrait of Reuther\n| birth_name = Walter Philip Reuther\n| birth_date = September 1, 1907\n| birth_place = [[Wheeling, West Virginia]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1970|5|9|1907|9|1}}\n| death_place = [[Pellston, Michigan]], U.S.\n| death_cause = Plane crash\n| other_names = \n| known_for = [[labor movement]], [[civil rights movement]]\n| office1 = 4th President of the [[United Automobile Workers]]\n| term_start1 = 1946\n| term_end1 = 1970\n| predecessor1 = [[R.J. Thomas]]\n| successor1 = [[Leonard F. Woodcock]]\n| signature = Walter_Reuther_Signature_Darker_and_Transparent_Background.xcf\n| office2 = 3rd President of the [[Congress of Industrial Organizations]]\n| term_start2 = 1952\n| term_end2 = 1955\n| predecessor2 = [[Philip Murray]]\n| successor2 = [[George Meany]]\n| occupation = [[Labor leader]]\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| awards = {{ubl|[[File:Presidential Medal of Freedom (ribbon).png|border|23px]] [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] (Posthumous; 1995)|[[Weizmann Institute of Science|Weizmann Award]]|[[Eugene V. Debs Award]]|[[Labor Hall of Honor]]|[[Automotive Hall of Fame]]}}\n| nationality = American\n| education = [[Wayne State University]] (withdrew)\n| spouse = {{marriage | May Wolf |1936}}\n| children = {{hlist|Linda|Elisabeth}}\n| parents = {{ubl|Valentine Reuther|Anna Stocker}}\n| relatives = {{ubl|[[Victor G. Reuther|Victor Reuther]]|Roy Reuther|Ted Reuther|Christine Reuther}}\n}}\n\n'''Walter Philip Reuther''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|u\u02d0|\u03b8|\u0259r}}; September 1, 1907 \u2013 May 9, 1970) was an American leader of [[Labor unions in the United States|organized labor]] and [[Civil rights movements|civil rights]] activist who built the [[United Automobile Workers]] (UAW) into one of the most [[Progressivism|progressive]] labor unions in American history.<ref name=\"United States Department of Labor\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dol.gov/general/aboutdol/hallofhonor/1990_reuther|title=Hall of Honor Inductee: Walter P. Reuther|date=December 9, 2015|work=United States Department of Labor|access-date=February 22, 2018|language=en}}</ref> He saw labor movements not as narrow special interest groups but as instruments to advance [[social justice]] and [[human rights]] in democratic societies.<ref name=\"United States Department of Labor\"/> He leveraged the UAW's resources and influence to advocate for [[United States labor law|workers' rights]], civil rights, [[women's rights]], [[universal health care]], [[Education in the United States|public education]], [[affordable housing]], [[Environmental movement in the United States|environmental stewardship]] and [[Nuclear proliferation|nuclear nonproliferation]] around the world.<ref name=\"United States Department of Labor\"/> He survived two attempted assassinations, including one at home where he was struck by a 12-gauge shotgun blast fired through his kitchen window.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://reuther100.wayne.edu/bio.php?pg=3|title=Walter P. Reuther|website=reuther100.wayne.edu|access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> He was the fourth and longest serving president of the UAW, serving from 1946 until his untimely death in 1970.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aflcio.org/about/history/labor-history-people/walter-reuther|title=Walter Reuther {{!}} AFL-CIO|website=aflcio.org|language=en|access-date=March 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA powerful ally of [[Martin Luther King Jr.|Martin Luther King, Jr.]] and the civil rights movement,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://billmoyers.com/content/meet-the-march-organizers/9/|title=Meet the 1963 March on Washington Organizers {{!}} BillMoyers.com|work=BillMoyers.com|access-date=February 25, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Reuther marched with King in [[Detroit Walk to Freedom|Detroit]], [[Selma to Montgomery marches|Selma]],<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.uawregion8.net/Activist-HOF/WReuther.htm|title=Region 8|website=www.uawregion8.net|access-date=March 1, 2018}}</ref> [[Birmingham campaign|Birmingham]],<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://kinginstitute.stanford.edu/encyclopedia/reuther-walter-philip|title=Reuther, Walter Philip|website=kinginstitute.stanford.edu|access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref> [[Selma to Montgomery marches|Montgomery]],<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Putting the World Together: My Father Walter Reuther: The Liberal Warrior|last=Dickmeyer, Reuther|first=Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=Living Force|year=|isbn=9780975379219|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/339 339]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/339}}</ref> and [[March Against Fear|Jackson]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://reuther.wayne.edu/node/7829|title=Walter P. Reuther Library (225427) Civil Rights, Demonstrations, \"Meredith March Against Fear,\" Mississippi, 1966|website=reuther.wayne.edu|language=en|access-date=March 1, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=Putting the World Together: My Father Walter Reuther: The Liberal Warrior|last=Dickmeyer|first=Reuther, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Publishing|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Michigan|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/350 350]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/350}}</ref> When King and others including children were jailed in [[Birmingham campaign|Birmingham, Alabama]], and King authored his famous [[Letter from Birmingham Jail]], Reuther arranged $160,000 for the protestors' release.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|title=Putting the World Together: My Father Walter Reuther: The Liberal Warrior|last=Dickmeyer|first=Reuther, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Publishing|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Michigan|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/237 237]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/237}}</ref> He also helped organize and finance the [[March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom|March on Washington]] on August 28, 1963, delivering remarks from the steps of the [[Lincoln Memorial]] shortly before King gave his historic \"[[I Have a Dream]]\" speech on the [[National Mall]].<ref name=\":2\"/><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=http://billmoyers.com/content/meet-the-march-organizers/9/|title=Meet the 1963 March on Washington Organizers {{!}} BillMoyers.com|work=BillMoyers.com|access-date=February 25, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> He served on the board of directors for the [[NAACP|National Association for the Advancement of Colored People]] (NAACP)<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://whospeaks.library.vanderbilt.edu/sites/default/files/WilkinsToWarren27Nov64.pdf|title=NAACP letterhead from November 24,1964, listing board members|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> and was one of the founders of [[Americans for Democratic Action]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://adaction.org/ada-history/|title=ADA's History \u2013 Americans for Democratic Action|work=Americans for Democratic Action|access-date=March 1, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> An early supporter of [[Cesar Chavez]] and the [[United Farm Workers]], he asked [[Robert F. Kennedy]] to visit and support Chavez.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The 100 greatest Americans of the 20th century : a social justice hall of fame|last=1948-|first=Dreier, Peter|date=2012|publisher=Nation Books|isbn=9781568586816|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/339 339]|oclc=701015405|url=https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/339}}</ref> A lifetime environmentalist, Reuther played a critical role in funding and organizing the first [[Earth Day]] on April 22, 1970.<ref name=\"Grist\">{{Cite news|url=https://grist.org/article/2010-04-21-labor-and-environmentalists-have-been-teaming-up-since-the-first/full/|title=Labor and environmentalists have been teaming up since the first Earth Day|date=April 22, 2010|work=Grist|access-date=February 24, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> According to [[Denis Hayes]], the principal national organizer of the first Earth Day, \"Without the UAW, the first Earth Day would have likely flopped!\"<ref name=\"Grist\"/>\n\nAs the leader of five million autoworkers including retirees and their families,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/383 383]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/383}}</ref> Reuther was influential inside the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The reckoning|first=David|last=Halberstam|date=1986|publisher=Morrow|isbn=9780688048389|edition=  1st|location=New York|pages=345|oclc=13861133}}</ref> During [[World War II]], President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] frequently consulted Reuther, referring to him as \"my young red-headed engineer.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The 100 greatest Americans of the 20th century : a social justice hall of fame|last=1948\u2013|first=Dreier, Peter|date=2012|publisher=Nation Books|isbn=9781568586816|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/233 233]|oclc=701015405|url=https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/233}}</ref> He was considered by [[John F. Kennedy]] for Vice President in 1960.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/3491219/behind-the-picture-jfk-and-rfk-los-angeles-july-1960/|title=Head to Head: JFK and RFK, Los Angeles, July 1960|last=Cosgrove|first=Ben|website=Time|language=en-us|access-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> Following the [[Bay of Pigs Invasion|Bay of Pigs]] in 1961, JFK sent Reuther to Cuba to negotiate a prisoner exchange with [[Fidel Castro]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/25/business/media/robert-boyd-dead.html|title=Robert Boyd, Journalist Whose Reporting Shifted an Election, Dies at 91|last=Roberts|first=Sam|date=September 25, 2019|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 5, 2019}}</ref> He was instrumental in spearheading the creation of the [[Peace Corps]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Walter Reuther|last=1943\u2013|first=Carew, Anthony|date=1993|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=9780719021886|location=Manchester|pages=101|oclc=27676666}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stanforddailyarchive.com/cgi-bin/stanford?a=d&d=stanford19640407-02.2.6|title=The Stanford Daily 7 April 1964 \u2014 The Stanford Daily|website=stanforddailyarchive.com|access-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The UAW and the heyday of American liberalism, 1945\u20131968|last=1960\u2013|first=Boyle, Kevin|date=1995|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801485381|location=Ithaca|pages=[https://archive.org/details/uawheydayofameri0000boyl/page/144 144]|oclc=32626436|url=https://archive.org/details/uawheydayofameri0000boyl/page/144}}</ref> and in marshaling support for the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/18/books/review/an-idea-whose-time-has-come-and-the-bill-of-the-century.html|title='An Idea Whose Time Has Come' and 'The Bill of the Century'|last=Boyle|first=Kevin|date=May 15, 2014|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 8, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"1948\u20132012 235\">{{Cite book|title=The 100 greatest Americans of the 20th century : a social justice hall of fame|last=1948\u2013|first=Dreier, Peter|date=2012|publisher=Nation Books|isbn=9781568586816|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/235 235]|oclc=701015405|url=https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/235}}</ref> the [[Voting Rights Act of 1965]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=The 100 greatest Americans of the 20th century : a social justice hall of fame|last=1948-|first=Dreier, Peter|date=2012|publisher=Nation Books|isbn=9781568586816|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/235 235]|oclc=701015405|url=https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/235}}</ref> [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] and [[Medicaid]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ssa.gov/history/LBJ/lbj.html|title=Social Security History|website=www.ssa.gov|language=en|access-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> and the [[Fair Housing Act]].<ref name=\"1948\u20132012 235\"/> He met weekly in 1964 and 1965 with President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] at the [[White House]] to discuss policies and legislation for the [[Great Society]] and [[War on Poverty]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/248 248]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/248}}</ref> The [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] was wary of Reuther, leading presidential candidate [[Richard Nixon]] to say about John F. Kennedy during the 1960 election, \"I can think of nothing so detrimental to this nation than for any President to owe his election to, and therefore be a captive of, a political boss like Walter Reuther.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Reuther|last=Frank.|first=Cormier|date=1970|publisher=Prentice-Hall|others=Eaton, William J.|isbn=9780137793143|location=Englewood Cliffs, N.J.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/376 376]|oclc=91809|url=https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/376}}</ref> Conservative politician [[Barry Goldwater]] declared that \"[Reuther] was more dangerous to our country than Sputnik or anything Soviet Russia might do.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The conscience of a liberal|last=Krugman|first=Paul R.|date=2007|publisher=W.W. Norton & Co|isbn=9780393333138|edition=1st|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/conscienceoflib00krug/page/111 111]|oclc=154706837|url=https://archive.org/details/conscienceoflib00krug/page/111}}</ref>\n\nReuther was posthumously awarded the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] in 1995 by President [[Bill Clinton]], who remarked at the ceremony, \"Walter Reuther was an American visionary so far ahead of his times that although he died a quarter of a century ago, our Nation has yet to catch up to his dreams.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Public Papers of the Presidents of the United States, William J. Clinton|last=|first=|publisher=United States Government Printing Office|year=1996|isbn=|location=|pages=Book II, page 1516}}</ref> Reuther was recognized by [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']] Magazine as one of the 100 most influential people of the 20th century.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,26473,00.html|title=TIME 100 Persons of The Century|date=June 6, 1999|work=Time|access-date=February 22, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0040-781X}}</ref> [[Murray Kempton]], a Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist, wrote, \"Walter Reuther is the only man I have ever met who could reminisce about the future.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oOo7DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA562&lpg=PA562&dq=Walter+Reuther+is+the+only+man+I+have+met+who+could+reminisce+about+the+future&source=bl&ots=ZmkISezp6v&sig=ACfU3U24zZeRD0gZsbq0ttsOxZCkY5tiHg&hl=en&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiVi6WS_f7mAhVOrp4KHT0qD7kQ6AEwCnoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=Walter%20Reuther%20is%20the%20only%20man%20I%20have%20met%20who%20could%20reminisce%20about%20the%20future&f=false|title=Whip: Leading the Progressive Battle During the Rise of the Right|last=Bonier|first=David|date=|website=www.presidency.ucsb.edu|page=562|url-status=live|archive-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oOo7DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA562&lpg=PA562&dq=Walter+Reuther+is+the+only+man+I+have+met+who+could+reminisce+about+the+future&source=bl&ots=ZmkISezp6v&sig=ACfU3U24zZeRD0gZsbq0ttsOxZCkY5tiHg&hl=en&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiVi6WS_f7mAhVOrp4KHT0qD7kQ6AEwCnoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=Walter%20Reuther%20is%20the%20only%20man%20I%20have%20met%20who%20could%20reminisce%20about%20the%20future&f=false|archive-date=|access-date=February 26, 2018}}</ref> [[A. H. Raskin]], labor editor of [[The New York Times]], wrote, \"If the speed of a man's mind could be measured in the same way as the speed of his legs, Walter Reuther would be an Olympic champion.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/88 88]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/88}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/GPO-CRECB-1970-pt16/pdf/GPO-CRECB-1970-pt16-4-1.pdf|title=Congressional Record, House of Representatives, Statement by Irving Bluestone|last=|first=|date=June 29, 1970|website=U.S. Government Publishing Office|page=21886|accessdate=March 4, 2018}}</ref> [[George W. Romney|George Romney]], Governor of Michigan, once said, \"Walter Reuther is the most dangerous man in Detroit because no one is more skillful in bringing about the revolution without seeming to disrupt the existing forms of society.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The 100 greatest Americans of the 20th century : a social justice hall of fame|last=1948\u2013|first=Dreier, Peter|date=2012|publisher=Nation Books|isbn=9781568586816|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/234 234]|oclc=701015405|url=https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/234}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nReuther was born on September 1, 1907, in [[Wheeling, West Virginia]], to Anna (n\u00e9e Stocker) and Valentine Reuther, who were [[German-Americans]].<ref>http://www.biography.com/people/walter-reuther-21402271</ref> His father Valentine was a horse-drawn beer wagon driver and [[Socialist Party of America|Socialist]] union organizer who at age 11 had emigrated from [[Germany]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/14 14]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/14}}</ref> Walter was one of five children, oldest to youngest: Ted, Walter, Roy, Victor, Christine. Valentine would facilitate debates every Sunday for his sons, training them to think on their feet about social issues of the day such as yellow journalism, child labor, women's suffrage, and civil rights.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW : a memoir|last=Reuther|first=Victor G.|date=1978|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=9780395275153|edition=  UAW special|location=Boston|pages=36\u201337|oclc=26295254}}</ref> Reuther later recalled, \"At my father's knee we learned the philosophy of trade unionism. We got the struggles, the hopes and the aspirations of working people every day.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://reuther100.wayne.edu/bio.php|title=Walter P. Reuther|website=reuther100.wayne.edu|access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref> As a child, he and Victor accompanied their father on a visit to a jail to meet [[Eugene V. Debs]], who was being incarcerated for his pacifism during World War I.<ref name=\"Raskin\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/06/13/archives/the-brothers-reuther.html|title=The Brothers Reuther|last=Raskin|first=A. H.|date=June 13, 1976|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 18, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>[[File:Reuther brothers busts.jpg|thumb|The Reuther brothers' busts at the Walter and May Reuther UAW Family Education Center in northern Michigan. From left to right, Roy Reuther, Walter Reuther, and Victor Reuther.]]\n\nThe Reuthers were frugal and learned not to waste. To save money, Walter's mother Anna would make underwear for her sons out of used flour sacks.<ref name=\"Halberstam 1986 339\">{{Cite book|title=The reckoning|last=Halberstam|first=David|date=1986|publisher=Morrow|year=|isbn=9780688048389|edition=1st|location=New York|pages=336|oclc=13861133}}</ref> When Valentine was partially blinded by an exploding bottle, Walter began doing odd jobs to bring in family income at the age of nine. He later dropped out of high school during his junior year and worked in a local factory to help support the family.<ref name=\"Halberstam 1986 339\"/> He learned firsthand about inadequate worker safety when a 400 pound die that he and three other men were lifting fell and severed his big toe.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/18 18]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/18}}</ref>\n\nFrom an early age, the Reuther boys received lessons on racism. One day they saw local boys throwing rocks at black people being transported north through their hometown in open railways cars. Their father gave them a stern warning to never treat another human being like that. The Reuther boys never forgot that lesson, spending the rest of their lives fighting for racial and economic equality for all people.<ref>{{Cite book|title=LIFE AND TIMES OF WALTER REUTHER.|last=JAMES.|first=TENEYCK|date=2016|publisher=PAGE PUBLISHING, INC|isbn=9781683482086|location=[S.l.]|pages=264|oclc=975986306}}</ref>\n\n=== Left home for Detroit ===\nIn 1927, at the age of 19, Reuther left Wheeling for Detroit and argued himself into an expert [[tool and die maker]] job at [[Ford Motor Company]] that required 25 years experience. The foreman was baffled that at his young age he could read blueprints and dies, becoming one of the highest paid mechanics in the factory.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW : a memoir|last=Reuther|first= Victor G |date=1978|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=9780395275153|edition=  UAW special |location=Boston|pages=46\u201348|oclc=26295254}}</ref> He finished high school while working at Ford and enrolled at Detroit City College, which is today known as [[Wayne State University]]. In 1932, he was fired for organizing a rally for [[Norman Thomas]] who was running for President of the United States as the nominee for the [[Socialist Party of America]]. His official Ford employment record states that he quit voluntarily, but Reuther himself maintained that he was fired for his increasingly visible socialist activities.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The most dangerous man in Detroit : Walter Reuther and the fate of American labor|last=Nelson.|first=Lichtenstein|date=1995|publisher=Basic Books|isbn=9780465090808|location=New York, NY|oclc=32468620|url=https://archive.org/details/mostdangerousman00lich}}</ref> Regardless, Walter and Victor decided it was the perfect time to fulfill their childhood dream and travel the world.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/25 25]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/25}}</ref>\n\n=== European trip ===\n\nWhen [[Henry Ford]] retired the [[Ford Model T|Model T]] in 1927, he sold the production mechanisms to Russia and American workers who knew how to operate the equipment were needed. Walter and Victor were promised work teaching Russian workers how to run the machines and assembly line. With that employment assurance, the brothers embarked on a three-year adventure, first bicycling through Europe, then working in the auto plant in [[Gorky, Russia]] where the unheated factories were often 30\u201340 degrees Fahrenheit below zero. He frequently wrote letters to the Moscow Daily News criticizing the many inefficiencies associated with how the communists operated the plants.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW : a memoir|last=Reuther |first= Victor G.|date=1978|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=9780395275153|edition=  UAW special |location=Boston|pages=88\u2013103|oclc=26295254}}</ref>\n\nAfter almost two years in Russia, the brothers travelled through Turkey, Iran, India, and China. After crossing the China Sea, they finished their Far East tour by bicycling throughout Japan. Finally, after being gone from home for almost three years, they found work for passage on the steamship President Harding to San Francisco and hurried back to Detroit where their brother Roy was already deeply involved with organizing autoworkers. Walter later stated the world tour taught him that \"all people long for the same basic human goals of a job with some degree of security, greater opportunity for their children, and of course, freedom. We felt we could make a contribution by helping American workers build strong and democratic labor unions. That's why we went into the labor movement.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/34 34]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/34}}</ref>\n\n===Political affiliation===\nBefore joining the Democratic Party, Reuther was a member of the Socialist Party of America. And, although Reuther always denied it, people including [[J. Edgar Hoover]], have suspected that at one time he was a member of the Communist Party.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Walter Reuther|last=Carew|first=Anthony|publisher=Manchester University Press|year=1993|isbn=071902188X|location=|pages=86}}</ref> On this subject, Reuther said in 1938, \"I am not and never have been a member of the Communist Party nor a supporter of its policies nor subject to its control or influence in any way.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Devinatz|first=Victor|date=2002|title=Reassessing The Historical UAW: Walter Reuther's Affiliation with the Communist Party and Something of Its Meaning \u2014 A Document of Party Involvement, 1939|url=http://www.lltjournal.ca/index.php/llt/article/view/5257|journal=Labour / Le Travail|volume=49|pages=225\u2013226|via=}}</ref> Nevertheless, people have suspected that he may have paid dues to the Communist Party for some months in 1935-36 and one source listed him as attending a Communist Party planning meeting as late as February 1939.<ref>Victor G. Devinatz, \n \"Reassessing the Historical UAW: Walter Reuther's Affiliation with the Communist Party and Something of Its Meaning: A Document of Party Involvement, 1939.\" ''Labour/Le Travail'' 49 (2002): 223-245. [https://journals.lib.unb.ca/index.php/LLT/article/viewFile/5257/6127 online] and also [https://www.jstor.org/stable/25149221 online at JSTOR] Devinatz says that he must have left the Party later in 1939.</ref> Reuther did cooperate with the Communists in the mid 1930s; this was the period of the [[Popular Front]], and the Communist Party agreed with him on internal issues of the UAW; but his associations were with anti-Stalinist Socialists.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/walterreuthermos00lich|url-access=registration|title=Walter Reuther: The Most Dangerous Man in Detroit|publisher=University of Illinois Press|author=Nelson Lichtenstein|year=1997|pages=[https://archive.org/details/walterreuthermos00lich/page/54 54]\u201356}}</ref><ref>Nelson Lichtenstein states, \" Reuther worked very closely with the Communists during this period, but he did not actually join the party.\" in Lichtenstein \"Reuther the Red?\" ''Labour/Le Travail'' 51 (2003) pp 165=69 at p 165.</ref> Reuther remained active in the Socialist Party and in 1937 failed in his attempt to be elected to the Detroit City Council when the AFL and blacks opposed his CIO ticket.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/walterreuthermos00lich|url-access=registration|title=Walter Reuther|publisher=University of Illinois Press|author=Lichtenstein|year=1997|pages=[https://archive.org/details/walterreuthermos00lich/page/87 87]\u201391}}</ref> However, impressed by the efforts by President Franklin D. Roosevelt to tackle inequality, he eventually joined the Democratic Party.\n\n== United Automobile Workers ==\n=== First victory against automobile companies ===\nUpon returning from Europe to Detroit, Reuther hitchhiked to [[South Bend, Indiana]] to attend the second annual convention as a delegate of the fledgling UAW. Upon his return he became president of newly formed Local 174 on Detroit's west side and with brother Victor, led the first successful strike against the automotive giants at Kelsey Hayes, which supplied brake drums and wheels to Ford Motor Company. The main complaint was the speed-up of the assembly line was intolerable. Workers were losing limbs and even their own lives trying in vain to keep up with the ever-increasing speed of the assembly line. It was December 1936 when the workers pulled a surprise strike and sat down in the plant refusing to leave until management negotiated with their representative, Walter Reuther.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Reuther|last=Frank.|first=Cormier|date=1970|publisher=Prentice-Hall|others=Eaton, William J.|isbn=9780137793143|location=Englewood Cliffs, N.J.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/70 70\u201373]|oclc=91809|url=https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/70}}</ref>\n\nWhen management tried to enter the plant to remove the machinery, thousands of sympathizers swarmed the sidewalks and blocked the doorways. Ford needed those brake drums and wheels badly and after 10 days of striking the sides settled. The first major UAW victory to unionize the auto factories was won. Upon Reuther's insistence, women won equal pay for equal work: 75 cents an hour. The speed-up of the assembly line was slowed down and the company could not fire a worker for joining the union. UAW Local 174's membership expanded from 200 before the strike to 35,000 within the next year.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/39 39\u201341]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/39}}</ref>\n\n=== General Motors ===\nIn 1936, [[General Motors]] (GM) was the largest corporation in the world and held many plants in [[Flint, Michigan]], about 60 miles north of Detroit. Reuther's brother, Roy, was already in Flint drawing up strategy plans and organizing workers to shut down the automaker until it would recognize the rights of the workers to unionize. The strike began on New Year's Eve, December 31, 1936 when the workers sat down in the plants and refused to leave. General Motors retaliated by turning off the heat in the plant.\n\nIn solidarity with the Flint strikers, Reuther led a strike at Detroit's Fleetwood Plant, where bodies were made for GM's luxury vehicle, the Cadillac. Support strikes were also called in Oakland, California, Pontiac, Michigan and St. Louis, Missouri. Autoworkers around the nation engaged in action in support of the Flint sit-down strikers.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW : a memoir|last=Reuther |first= Victor G.|date=1978|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=9780395275153|edition=  UAW special |location=Boston|pages=150|oclc=26295254}}</ref>\n\nBack in Flint, the police tried to force the workers out of the plant in what became known as the \"Battle of Bulls Run.\" Over a hundred policemen attacked the pickets with tear gas and bullets, sending thirteen workers to the hospital with gunshot wounds. Victor manned the sound car and encouraged the workers to fight back, which they did by sling-shotting door hinges from the factory roof and turning fire hoses on the police in the 16-degree Fahrenheit winter night. Victor and Genora Johnson, a leader of the Women's Brigade, took turns in the sound car exhorting the workers to stand their ground.\n\nMichigan Governor, [[Frank Murphy]], called in 2,000 members of the National Guard, not to force the workers out of the plants, but to keep the peace. After a brilliant move, the workers were able to gain control of the only plant in the country that made [[Chevrolet]] engines. Finally, 44 days later, General Motors was forced to recognize the worker's right to unionize and signed its first collective bargaining agreement with the fledgling UAW.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW : a memoir|last=Reuther |first= Victor G.|date=1978|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=9780395275153|edition=  UAW special |location=Boston|oclc=26295254}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Flint sit-down strike|Flint Sit-Down Strike]] has become known as the Lexington and Valley Forge of American industrial unionism. Roy recalled, \"When the boys came out of the plants, I never saw a night like that and perhaps will never see it again. I liken it to a country experiencing independence, families reunited for the first time since the strike began, kids hanging onto daddy with tears of joy and happiness. It was a sea of humanity in which fears were no longer on the minds of the workers.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/51 51]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/51}}</ref>\n\nIn 1950, Reuther negotiated and signed with [[Charles Erwin Wilson|Charlie Wilson]], chief executive officer of General Motors, the [[Reuther's Treaty of Detroit|Treaty of Detroit]], an historic five-year labor contract that, in exchange for a commitment not to strike, gave rank-and-file workers better wages, health care, and pensions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/remembering-the-legacy-of-labor-day/2019/09/01/8c67cd08-cb2f-11e9-be05-f76ac4ec618c_story.html|title=Remembering the Legacy of Labor Day|last=Dionne Jr.|first=E.J.|date=September 2, 2019|website=Washington Post|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At the time, Fortune Magazine wrote that the Treaty of Detroit \u201cmade the worker to an amazing degree a middle class member of a middle class society.\u201d<ref>{{Cite book|title=America in Our Time: From World War II to Nixon--what Happened and why|last=Hodgson|first=Godfrey|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=1976|isbn=0691122881|location=|pages=82}}</ref>\n\n=== Chrysler ===\n[[Chrysler]] was next on the list of the young UAW. In March 1937, 60,000 Chrysler workers went on strike. When police started roughing up pickets and strikers, over 150,000 citizens gathered at Detroit's downtown Cadillac Square where Reuther and others led them in protest. After a four-week strike, Chrysler followed General Motors\u2019 lead and negotiated its first collective bargaining agreement with the UAW.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/52 52\u201353]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/52}}</ref>\n\n=== Ford Motor Company ===\n[[Henry Ford]] had stated that he would never allow his workers to unionize. His main enforcer was [[Harry Bennett]], who led a 3,000 man Security Department for Ford Motor Company, whose mandate was to intimidate, beat, and fire any worker who showed signs of favoring unionization. In 1932, when workers marched out of the giant [[Ford River Rouge Complex]] in protest to the speed-up of the assembly lines, they were attacked by Bennett's armed men and 5 workers were shot dead and hundreds suffered injuries.<ref>{{Cite book|title=LIFE AND TIMES OF WALTER REUTHER.|last=JAMES.|first=TENEYCK|date=2016|publisher=PAGE PUBLISHING, INC|isbn=9781683482086|location=[S.l.]|pages=212|oclc=975986306}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Labor-Strike-Ford Motor Company-Walter Reuther fifth from the left-Richard Frankensteen sixth from the left - NARA - 195593.tif|thumb|Battle of the Overpass, May 26, 1937, Walter Reuther fifth from left, Richard Frankensteen sixth from left]]\nBarely a month after the Chrysler signing, Reuther got permission from the [[Dearborn, Michigan|City of Dearborn]] to pass out handbills titled, \"Unionism, not Fordism\" on public property at Gate Four of the giant [[Ford River Rouge Complex]]. As he and three other UAW leaders climbed the stairs to the bridge, they were attacked by Bennett's \"enforcers\" who severely beat them.<ref>{{Cite book|title=LIFE AND TIMES OF WALTER REUTHER.|last=JAMES.|first=TENEYCK|date=2016|publisher=PAGE PUBLISHING, INC|isbn=9781683482086|location=[S.l.]|pages=214\u2013216|oclc=975986306}}</ref>\n\nReuther was instantly surrounded by at least a dozen men, knocked to the ground, kicked and punched in the head and body, picked up 4 feet parallel to the ground then slammed to the concrete repeatedly, then thrown and kicked down 3 flights of stairs. The pummeling continued as 4 or 5 men beat him in and out of parked cars, until a streetcar arrived with union women to pass out leaflets and the thugs turned their attention to viciously attack them.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/56 56]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/56}}</ref>\n\nPress photographers were attacked as well and their camera's confiscated but one camera was inconspicuously thrown into a convertible and the next day, the \"[[Battle of the Overpass]],\" was national news.\n\nThe beatings taken by the union organizers in the long run hurt Henry Ford more, as national sentiment turned against him. ''Time'' magazine published the photographs with descriptions of how the union men and women were mercilessly beaten by Henry Ford's paid thugs. Ford retaliated against ''Time'', ''Life'', and ''Fortune'' magazines by withdrawing all advertising.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Reuther|last=Frank.|first=Cormier|date=1970|publisher=Prentice-Hall|others=Eaton, William J.|isbn=9780137793143|location=Englewood Cliffs, N.J.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/103 103\u2013107]|oclc=91809|url=https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/103}}</ref>\n\nIt took four more years, but finally, in 1941, Henry Ford signed his first agreement with the UAW. Shortly after, Henry Ford told Walter Reuther: \"It was one of the most sensible things Harry Bennett ever did when he got the UAW into this plant.\" Reuther inquired, \"What do you mean?\" Ford replied, \"Well, you've been fighting General Motors and the Wall Street crowd. Now you're in here and we've given you a union shop and more than you got out of them. That puts you on our side, doesn't it? We can fight General Motors and Wall Street together, eh?\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/63 63]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/63}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1950s, Reuther and [[Henry Ford II]], CEO of Ford, toured a state-of-the-art engine plant in Cleveland. As they walked about the plant, Ford gestured to the cutting-edge, automated machines, saying, \"Walter, how are you going to get these robots to pay union dues?\" Without missing a beat, Reuther famously replied: \"Henry, how are you going to get them to buy your cars?\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2015/07/world-without-work/395294/|title=A World Without Work|last=Thompson|first=Derek|work=The Atlantic|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== \"500 Planes a Day\" ===\nIn 1940, in the midst of [[World War II]], the United States was producing fighter planes to help the allies in their war against [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler's]] aggression. The production was slow, inadequate, and threatening the security of the Allies. The US planned to construct new manufacturing plants specifically to produce more planes. That plan, however, would have taken two years to begin producing planes. The Allies did not have that time to spare. In response, Reuther proposed \"to transform the entire unused capacity of the auto industry into one huge plane production unit capable of turning out 500 Planes a Day.\" After getting the support of workers, he publicly announced the \"Reuther Plan: 500 Planes a Day,\" shortly before Christmas, 1940.<ref>{{Cite book|title=FDR, the war president, 1940\u20131943 : a history|last=1912\u20131999.|first=Davis, Kenneth S. (Kenneth Sydney)|date=2000|publisher=Random House|others=Rogers D. Spotswood Collection.|isbn=9780679415428|edition=1st|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/fdrwarpresident100davi/page/436 436]|oclc=43694290|url=https://archive.org/details/fdrwarpresident100davi/page/436}}</ref> He said, during a national radio address on December 28, 1940:\n\n<blockquote>In London they are huddled in the subways praying for aid from America. In America we are huddled over blueprints praying that Hitler will be obliging enough to postpone an \"all out\" attack on England for another two years until new plants finally begin to turn out engines and aircraft. We believe that without disturbing present aircraft plant production schedules we can supplement them by turning out 500 planes a day of a single standard fighting model by the use of idle automotive capacity. . . . England's battles, it used to be said, were won on the playing fields of Eton. America's can be won on the assembly lines of Detroit. Give England planes and there will be no need to give her men.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://reuther100.wayne.edu/pdf/500_Planes_Speech.pdf|title=More Airplanes for Defense|last=Reuther|first=Walter|date=|website=Walter P. Reuther Library|access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nA week after receiving the plan, on December 30, 1940, President Roosevelt wrote [[William S. Knudsen]], chairman of the [[War Production Board]], \"It is well worthwhile to give a good deal of attention to this (Reuther) program.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=FDR, the war president, 1940\u20131943 : a history|last=1912\u20131999.|first=Davis, Kenneth S. (Kenneth Sydney)|date=2000|publisher=Random House|others=Rogers D. Spotswood Collection.|isbn=9780679415428|edition=1st|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/fdrwarpresident100davi/page/437 437]|oclc=43694290|url=https://archive.org/details/fdrwarpresident100davi/page/437}}</ref> Three days later on January 2, 1941, Reuther met with President Roosevelt at the White House to discuss the possibility of implementing his plan for 500 Planes a Day.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/65 65]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/65}}</ref>\n\nGeneral Motors, Ford, and Chrysler all opposed the Reuther Plan because they wanted the government to build new plane and tank factories that could be sold to them at giveaway prices after the war.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/time-another-reuther-plan/|title=Time for Another Reuther Plan|last=Lichtenstein|first=Nelson|date=May 13, 2009|work=The Nation|access-date=March 3, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0027-8378}}</ref> They also disliked that labor had the audacity to stick their nose into production, which they felt was management's exclusive domain. [[Alfred P. Sloan]], chairman of General Motors, scoffed at the idea, stating, \"only about 10 to 15% of the machinery and equipment in an automobile factory can be utilized for the production of special defense material.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/66 66]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/66}}</ref>\n\nAfter the attack on [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|Pearl Harbor on December 7, 1941]], many of Reuther's proposals were implemented. Detroit's automobile plants produced planes and tanks in mass volume and became known as the center of the [[Arsenal of Democracy]], which gave the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] a decisive advantage to win the war. By 1943, Chrysler President, [[K. T. Keller]], reported that his company had converted 89% of its machine tools to wartime production, leading Washington Post publisher, [[Phil Graham]], to state that meant Reuther was 89% right.<ref>{{Cite book|title=LIFE AND TIMES OF WALTER REUTHER.|last=JAMES.|first=TENEYCK|date=2016|publisher=PAGE PUBLISHING, INC|isbn=9781683482086|location=[S.l.]|oclc=975986306}}</ref> At the war's end, ''Fortune'' magazine wrote: \"Reuther was right on track. Compared with many industrialists that sat back and hugged profits and the aimless agencies of Washington, the red-headed labor leader exhibited atomic spirit of action. He never let up.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/69 69]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/69}}</ref>\n\n=== Elected UAW president ===\nAfter the war ended in 1945, Reuther proved he would be a different type of labor leader when he led a strike challenging GM to increase workers wages by 30% without increasing the price of their new cars.&nbsp;Worker pay had been restricted during World War II and Reuther sought to get them a raise but not at the cost of increased inflation.&nbsp;Historically, when workers won a pay increase, the company would pass on the expense to their consumers.&nbsp;GM refused the pay increase and after a 113-day strike, the sides settled on an eighteen and a half cent hourly raise.&nbsp;Reuther's bold collective bargaining leadership in this strike catapulted him into the union's top position.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Reuther|last=Frank.|first=Cormier|date=1970|publisher=Prentice-Hall|others=Eaton, William J.|isbn=9780137793143|location=Englewood Cliffs, N.J.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/223 223\u2013230]|oclc=91809|url=https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/223}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 1946, Reuther won the election and became the president of the UAW in a very close race, defeating incumbent UAW president [[R. J. Thomas]] by a mere 124 votes, out of almost 9,000 cast. The new UAW president pledged his vision of \"a labor movement whose philosophy is to fight for the welfare of the public at large.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/81 81]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/81}}</ref> One of his first acts as president was to fight to integrate the American Bowling League, which had previously excluded black bowlers.&nbsp;He was a new kind of leader who viewed the labor movement as \"an instrument for social change.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/3 3]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/3}}</ref>\n\n==== Salary ====\nAlthough presidents of much smaller unions were making 3 or 4 times his salary, Reuther purposely kept his salary low to stay in touch, and show solidarity, with UAW members he represented. He never made an annual salary of more than $31,000. Author [[David Halberstam]] writes: \"His life was not about material things. The constant success of the union was reward enough.\"<ref name=\"Halberstam 1986 339\" />\n\n=== Expelling Communism from organized labor ===\nThe following 18 months after Reuther's election win, bitter battles erupted inside the UAW as Communist-backers of [[R. J. Thomas]] had a two-thirds majority on the UAW's Executive Board. One observer noted, \"The Commies threw everything but their hammer and sickle at Walter.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/85 85]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/85}}</ref> In November 1947, at the next UAW national convention, this time Reuther won the election overwhelmingly, severely weakening the Communist's hold on the union's leadership. ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine reported that Reuther's victory was \"the biggest setback of all time for the Communists in the American Labor Movement.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/86 86]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/86}}</ref>\n\nAs president, Reuther next sought to remove officers from Communist-dominated unions within the CIO, leading [[Hubert Humphrey]] to write,\"Communist infiltration of the CIO was a direct threat to the survival of all of our country's democratic institutions. The CIO's victory over the Communist party was a significant victory for our nation.\" In response, [[Trud (Russian newspaper)|Trud]], a Soviet newspaper, called Reuther a \"traitor and strikebreaker\" and a favorite of the [[United States Chamber of Commerce|U.S. Chamber of Commerce]]. The [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] called Reuther \"the most dangerous man in America and a Communist.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/86 86\u201387]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/86}}</ref> Despite removing Communists from the labor movement, [[J. Edgar Hoover]], Director of the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]], never stopped labeling Reuther a Communist for working in Russia and having early associations with Communists and Socialists. During World War II, J. Edgar Hoover considered subjecting Reuther, and his brothers Victor and Roy, to custodial detention.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/68 68]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/68}}</ref>\n\nIn 1959, at the request of the [[United States Department of State]], Reuther met with Soviet Premier [[Nikita Khrushchev]] to discuss, among other things, capitalism versus communism, organized labor, and US-Russia relations. The meeting happened in San Francisco at the [[Mark Hopkins Hotel]] and was front-page international news.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW : a memoir|last=Reuther |first= Victor G.|date=1978|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=9780395275153|edition=  UAW special |location=Boston|pages=395|oclc=26295254}}</ref> Later when Khrushchev met with President Kennedy at the [[Vienna summit|Vienna Summit]] in 1961, he told Kennedy, \"We hung the likes of Reuther in Russia in 1917.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW : a memoir|last=Reuther |first= Victor G.|date=1978|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=9780395275153|edition=  UAW special |location=Boston|pages=394\u201399|oclc=26295254}}</ref>\n\n=== Collective bargaining ===\nAs president of the UAW, Reuther negotiated contracts that included unprecedented standard-of-living increases for automobile workers. Such increases include annual raises based on productivity advances, cost-of-living increases, supplementary unemployment benefits, early-retirement options, and health and welfare benefits.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Walter-Reuther|title=Walter Reuther {{!}} American labour leader|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=March 17, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Photograph of President Truman in the Oval Office, conferring with labor leader Walter Reuther, president of the... - NARA - 200406.jpg|thumb|left|Walter Reuther (right) conferring with President Truman in the Oval Office, 1952]]\nHe employed a strategy called \"[[pattern bargaining]]\" against the [[Big Three (automobile manufacturers)|Big Three]] automobile manufacturers, [[General Motors]], [[Ford Motor Company]], and [[Chrysler]].<ref name=\"Alfred. 2009 149\">{{Cite book|title=The automobile and American life|last=Alfred.|first=Heitmann, John|date=2009|publisher=McFarland & Co|isbn=9780786440139|location=Jefferson, N.C.|pages=149|oclc=298304623}}</ref> He would first target a company that seemed most likely to accept his bargaining objective. If that target company refused offer concessions, Reuther would threaten a strike to halt production at its plants only while allowing production operations at its competitors' plants to go uninterrupted. As a result, the target company would accept Reuther's demands to prevent its competitors form absorbing its sales and market share. Once he secured the initial agreement, he would use it as a pattern against the other automobile companies, threatening to strike if they too did not match the same terms to which the initial target company agreed. Reuther employed pattern bargaining to leverage competition among automobile manufacturers, maximize the influence of labor, and reduce the frequency of costly strikes.<ref name=\"Alfred. 2009 149\"/>\n\nReuther tried to negotiate lower automobile prices for consumers with each contract, with limited success.<ref>Victor G. Reuther ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=zv2Nm7Ct17MC&q=The+Brothers+Reuther&dq=The+Brothers+Reuther&hl=en&sa=X&ei=7SvxTvTCOKLs0gHc-rGTAg&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAQ&safe=active The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW]'', p. 249</ref>\n\nAfter the [[bombing of Pearl Harbor]], Reuther strongly supported the war effort and refused to tolerate [[Wildcat strike action|wildcat strikes]] that might disrupt munitions production. He worked for the [[War Manpower Commission]], the Office of Production Management, and the [[War Production Board]].<ref>Arthur Herman, ''Freedom's Forge: How American Business Produced Victory in World War II,'' (2012) pp. 116\u201317, 196\u201397, 231.</ref> He led a [[United Auto Workers (UAW) strike of 1945-46|113-day strike]] against General Motors in 1945\u20131946; it only partially succeeded. He never received the power he wanted to inspect company books or have a say in management, but he achieved increasingly lucrative wage and benefits contracts.<ref>Michelle Brattain, \"Reuther, Walter Philip\"; ''American National Biography Online'' (2000)</ref>\n\nHe became president of the CIO in 1952, and negotiated a merger with [[George Meany]] and the American Federation of Labor immediately after, which took effect in 1955. In 1949 he led the CIO delegation to the London conference that set up the [[International Confederation of Free Trade Unions]] in opposition to the communist-dominated [[World Federation of Trade Unions]]. He had left the Socialist Party in 1939, and throughout the 1950s and 1960s was a leading spokesman for liberal interests in the CIO and in the Democratic Party.<ref name=\"Brattain 2000\">Brattain, \"Reuther, Walter Philip\"; ''American National Biography Online'' (2000)</ref>\n\n== Civil rights activism ==\n[[File:Photograph of White House Meeting with Civil Rights Leaders. June 22, 1963 - NARA - 194190 (no border).tif|thumb|Civil rights leaders with Vice President Johnson and Attorney General Robert Kennedy at the White House on June 22, 1963.]]Reuther was a strong supporter of the [[Civil Rights Movement]].<ref name=\":0\" /> He marched with King in [[Selma to Montgomery marches|Selma]],<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Birmingham campaign|Birmingham]],<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Selma to Montgomery marches|Montgomery]],<ref name=\":3\" /> and [[March Against Fear|Jackson]]<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> and when King and others were jailed in [[Birmingham campaign|Birmingham, Alabama]], and King authored his famous [[Letter from Birmingham Jail]], Reuther arranged $160,000 for the protestors' release.<ref name=\":6\" /> He also helped organize and finance the [[March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom|March on Washington]] on August 28, 1963, delivering remarks from the steps of the [[Lincoln Memorial]] shortly before King gave his historic \"[[I Have a Dream]]\" speech.<ref name=\":2\"/><ref name=\":8\" /> He served on the board of directors for the [[NAACP|National Association for the Advancement of Colored People]] (NAACP).<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nOn the 25th anniversary of the UAW, King wrote a letter to Reuther, congratulating him on his successes and observing:<blockquote>More than anyone else in America, you stand out as the shining symbol of democratic trade unionism. Through trials, efforts and your unswerving devotion to humanitarian causes, you have made life more meaningful for millions of working people. Through moments of difficulty and strong obstacles, you have stood firm for what you believe, knowing that in the long run 'Truth crushed to earth will rise again.' As I have heard you say, the true measure of a man is where he stands in moments of challenge and controversy, when the only consolation he gains is the quiet whisper of an inner voice saying there are things so eternally true and significant that they are worth dying for, if necessary. You have demonstrated over the years that you can stand up in moments of challenge and controversy. One day all of America will be proud of your achievements, and will record your work as one of the glowing epics of our heritage.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the World Together: My Father Walter Reuther, The Liberal Warrior|last=Reuther|first=Elisabeth|publisher=Living Force Publishing|year=2004|isbn=0975379216|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/190 190]|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/190}}</ref></blockquote>[[File:1963 march on washington.jpg|thumb|Leaders of the March on Washington]]\n\n[[Coretta Scott King]] later said, <blockquote>Walter Reuther was to black people, the most widely known and respected white labor leader in the nation. He was there when the storm clouds were thick.  We remember him in Montgomery. He was in Birmingham. He marched with us in Selma, and Jackson, Mississippi and in Washington.&nbsp;... Only yesterday, there he was again in Charleston, South Carolina, the leader of a million and a half workers giving personal support to a strike of only 400 black women.&nbsp;...  He was a big man, so of course he had enemies and detractors. He had the courage to be with the minority when it was right.  He was a simple man in his personal life, a rare quality in these flamboyant times&nbsp;... but if his ways were simple, his ideas were grand.  He aroused the imagination of millions.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/350 350\u201351]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/350}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn the early 1930s, Reuther first challenged racism as a student at what is now Wayne State University. When a local hotel, which had agreed with the college to let students use its swimming pool, refused to let blacks swim, he organized a picket line. The protest surrounded the block. As a result, the hotel closed its pool to all students.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Walter Reuther|last=1943\u2013|first=Carew, Anthony|date=1993|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=9780719021886|location=Manchester|pages=264|oclc=27676666}}</ref> In a 2013 interview with ''The New York Times'', President [[Barack Obama]] said, <blockquote>\"When you think about the coalition that brought about civil rights, it wasn\u2019t just folks who believed in racial equality; it was people who believed in working folks having a fair shot. It was Walter Reuther and the UAW coming down here because they understood that if there are some workers who are not getting a fair deal then ultimately that\u2019s going to undercut their ability to get a fair deal.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/28/us/politics/interview-with-president-obama.html|title=Interview with President Obama|last=|first=|date=July 27, 2013|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 22, 2019}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Walk to Freedom, June 23, 1963 ===\nThe [[Detroit Walk to Freedom|Walk to Freedom]] was a mass march during the [[Civil Rights Movement]] on June 23, 1963 in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]]. The purpose of the demonstration was to protest racism, segregation, and the brutality inflicted upon civil rights activists in the South as well as the discrimination facing African-Americans in the North such as inequality in hiring, wages, education, and housing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reuther.wayne.edu/node/7858|title=Walter P. Reuther Library|website=reuther.wayne.edu|language=en|access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref> In some ways, it was considered a dress rehearsal for the [[March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom]], which was scheduled for two months later.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Sweet land of liberty : the forgotten struggle for civil rights in the North|last=1962\u2013|first=Sugrue, Thomas J.|year=2008|isbn=9780679643036|edition=First|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/sweetlandofliber00sugr/page/298 298\u2013301]|oclc=191732290|url=https://archive.org/details/sweetlandofliber00sugr/page/298}}</ref> An estimated 125,000 people attended and it was the largest civil rights demonstration in the nation's history up to that date.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/local/michigan-history/2017/09/02/walter-reuther-uaw-giant/105249350/|title=Walter Reuther was labor legend on a global scale|work=Detroit News|access-date=March 18, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\nReuther mobilized support for the protest and donated office space at the UAW's headquarters Solidarity House for Martin Luther King, Jr. to organize the event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uawregion8.net/Activist-HOF/WReuther.htm|title=Region 8|website=www.uawregion8.net|access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref> Along with others, including King, Reuther marched down [[Woodward Avenue]] and delivered remarks afterwards at [[Cobo Center|Cobo Hall]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/detroits-forgotten-dream/2013/06/20/4ca4b61a-d868-11e2-a9f2-42ee3912ae0e_story.html|title=Detroit's forgotten 'Dream'|last=Maraniss|first=David|date=June 20, 2013|work=Washington Post|access-date=March 18, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> It was there that King delivered his first version of his \"I Have a Dream,\" speech, having penned it, at least partially, inside his office at Solidarity House.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://detroitnaacp.org/50th-anniversary-freedom-walk-detroit-press-conference/|title=50th Anniversary Freedom Walk Detroit Press Conference|last=|first=|date=June 10, 2013|website=Detroit NAACP|access-date=March 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.peoplesworld.org/article/detroit-remembers-50-years-after-king-s-i-have-a-dream-speech/|title=Detroit remembers 50 years after King's \"I Have a Dream\" speech|last=Rummel|first=John|date=June 11, 2013|website=Peoples World|access-date=March 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{external media | width = 210px | float = right | audio1 = [http://openvault.wgbh.org/collections/march_on_washington/ern-coverage Complete radio coverage of the March on Washington], August 28, 1963, Educational Radio Network<ref name=\"ern\">{{cite web | title =Special Collections, March on Washington, Parts 1\u201317 | work = Open Vault | publisher = at [[WGBH Educational Foundation|WGBH]] | date = August 28, 1963 | url =http://openvault.wgbh.org/collections/march_on_washington/ern-coverage |access-date= March 19, 2018 }}</ref>\n| audio2 = [http://openvault.wgbh.org/catalog/A_CB387942466C46F6BAE6528BAFD53055#at_2417.423_s Walter Reuther's remarks begin at 40:40], August 28, 1963, Educational Radio Network<ref name=\"ern2\">{{cite web | title =Special Collections, March on Washington, Part 17 | work = Open Vault | publisher = at [[WGBH Educational Foundation|WGBH]] | date = August 28, 1963 | url = http://openvault.wgbh.org/catalog/A_CB387942466C46F6BAE6528BAFD53055#at_2417.423_s | access-date= March 19, 2018 }}</ref>\n }}\n\n=== March on Washington, August 28, 1963 ===\n[[File:March-on-washington-jobs-freedom-program.jpg|thumb|Official program of March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom|271x271px]]The [[March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom]] was held in [[Washington, D.C.]] on Wednesday, August 28, 1963. The protest sought to advocate for the civil and economic rights of [[African American]]s. Along with the [[Big Six (activists)|Big Six]] and three white religious leaders, Reuther helped organize the march.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://kingencyclopedia.stanford.edu/encyclopedia/encyclopedia/enc_reuther_walter_philip_1907_1970/|title=Reuther, Walter Philip (1907\u20131970)|website=kingencyclopedia.stanford.edu|access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":8\" />  Originally, the march was planned to take place outside of the [[United States Capitol|Capitol Building]]. Reuther, however, persuaded the other organizers to move the march to the [[Lincoln Memorial]]. He believed the Lincoln Memorial would be less threatening to Congress and the occasion would be more appropriate underneath the gaze of Abraham Lincoln's statute. The committee, notably Rustin, agreed to move the site on the condition that Reuther pay for a $19,000 sound system so that everyone on the [[National Mall]] could hear the speakers and musicians.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Once in a great city : a Detroit story|last=David.|first=Maraniss|year=|isbn=9781476748399|edition=First Simon & Schuster hardcover|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/onceingreatcityd00mara/page/236 236]|oclc=894936463|url=https://archive.org/details/onceingreatcityd00mara/page/236}}</ref> \nReuther and the UAW financed bus transportation for 5,000 of its rank-and-file members, providing the largest single contingent from any organization.<ref>{{Cite book|title=American vanguard : the United Auto Workers during the Reuther years, 1935-1970|last=1932-|first=Barnard, John|date=2004|publisher=Wayne State University Press|isbn=9780814332979|location=Detroit|pages=388|oclc=52819692}}</ref> The UAW also paid for and brought thousands of signs for marchers to carry. Among other things, the signs read: \"There Is No Halfway House on the Road to Freedom,\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.colorlines.com/articles/1963-march-washington-photos|title=The 1963 March on Washington in Photos|last=cl_admin|date=August 23, 2013|work=Colorlines|access-date=March 21, 2018|language=en}}</ref> \"Equal Rights and Jobs NOW,\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/114408/march-washington-50th-anniversary-walter-reuthers-speech|title=The White Man Whose 'March on Washington' Speech You Should Remember Too|work=The New Republic|access-date=March 21, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> \"UAW Supports Freedom March,\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://americanhistory.si.edu/changing-america-emancipation-proclamation-1863-and-march-washington-1963/1963/march-washington|title=March on Washington|website=National Museum of American History|language=en|access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref> \"in Freedom we are Born, in Freedom we must Live,\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.com/melissa-harris-perry/how-womens-voices-were-excluded-the|title=How women's voices were excluded from the March|work=MSNBC|access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref> and \"Before we'll be a Slave, we'll be Buried in our Grave.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/EJ1021080.pdf|title=The Move to Unity, labor's role in the March on Washington|last=Jones|first=William|date=|website=|access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nReuther was the most prominent white organizer scheduled to speak. In his remarks, on the steps of the [[Lincoln Memorial]], he urged Americans to pressure their politicians to act to address racial injustices. He said:\n[[File:President John F. Kennedy and Vice President Lyndon B. Johnson Meet with Organizers of \"March on Washington\".jpg|thumb|[[John F. Kennedy|Kennedy]] and [[Lyndon B. Johnson|Johnson]] with organizers of the \"March on Washington\" at the White House on August 28, 1963 ]]\n\n<blockquote>American democracy is on trial in the eyes of the world\u2026 We cannot successfully preach democracy in the world unless we first practice democracy at home. American democracy will lack the moral credentials and be both unequal to and unworthy of leading the forces of freedom against the forces of tyranny unless we take bold, affirmative, adequate steps to bridge the moral gap between American democracy's noble promises and its ugly practices in the field of civil rights.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://billmoyers.com/content/meet-the-march-organizers/9/|title=Meet the 1963 March on Washington Organizers {{!}} BillMoyers.com|work=BillMoyers.com|access-date=2018-03-21|language=en-US}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nAccording to [[Irving Bluestone]], who was standing near the platform while Reuther delivered his remarks, he overheard two black women talking. One asked, \"Who is that white man?\" The other replied, \"Don't you know him? That's the white Martin Luther King.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jones|first=William|date=Fall 2013|title=The Move to Unity, Labor's Role in the March on Washington|url=https://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/EJ1021080.pdf|journal=American Educator|volume=|pages=35|via=}}</ref> After the march, the civil rights leaders met with President Kennedy at the White House to discuss civil rights legislation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jfklibrary.org/Asset-Viewer/lCuiXLZD20Go3B0o7rpWvg.aspx|title=President Kennedy with leaders of the March on Washington - John F. Kennedy Presidential Library & Museum|website=www.jfklibrary.org|access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Cesar Chavez and the United Farm Workers ===\nIn December 1965, Reuther visited [[Cesar Chavez]] and the striking grape growers in [[Delano, California|Delano]], [[California]]. Two months earlier, Reuther's brother and colleague, Roy, had visited the striking farmworkers. Upon returning from his visit, Roy urged Walter to support Chavez.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Cesar Chavez : autobiography of La Causa|last=E.|first=Levy, Jacques|date=2007|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|others=Chavez, Cesar, 1927-1993., Ross, Fred, Jr., Levy, Jacqueline M.|isbn=9780816650491|edition=  1st University of Minnesota Press |location=Minneapolis|pages=202|oclc=227339180}}</ref> At that time, Chavez's struggle for workers' rights was little known to the American public, but Reuther's visit garnered national media attention, making it difficult for the growers to ignore the striking grape pickers. During the trip, Reuther marched with Chavez and his fellow strikers, carrying picket signs reading \"Huelga.\" Reuther also spoke to packed union hall, declaring, \"This is not your strike, this is our strike!\" He pledged that the UAW would provide $7,500 per month to the [[United Farm Workers]]' strike fund for the duration of the strike.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Cesar Chavez|last=Hal.|first=Marcovitz|date=2003|publisher=Chelsea House Publishers|isbn=9780791072530|location=Philadelphia|pages=53\u201354|oclc=50913476}}</ref>\n\nUpon returning to Detroit, Reuther contacted Senator [[Robert F. Kennedy]], who was on the [[United States Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor and Pensions|Senate Labor Committee]], requesting that Kennedy visit Chavez in Delano to learn about and support the farmworkers. Kennedy obliged, ultimately becoming the most visible supporter of the farmworkers' movement.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The 100 greatest Americans of the 20th century : a social justice hall of fame|last=1948-|first=Dreier, Peter|date=2012|publisher=Nation Books|isbn=9781568586816|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/235 235, 339]|oclc=701015405|url=https://archive.org/details/100greatestameri0000drei/page/235}}</ref> Reuther visited Chavez many times, including once during Chavez's hunger strike. During that visit, Reuther made a $50,000 donation to Chavez's struggle to which Chavez said, \"Walter, you have given me great confidence.\" Reuther replied, \"You will prevail for your cause is just.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/287 287\u201388]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/287}}</ref> In honor of the Reuther brothers' early and sustained support, the United Farm Workers named a building at their Delano headquarters the \"Roy Reuther Administration Building.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/ca3945/|title=Forty Acres, Roy Reuther Administration Building, 30168 Garces Highway (Northwest Corner of Garces Highway and Mettler Avenue), Delano, Kern County, CA|work=The Library of Congress|access-date=March 22, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Assassination attempts ==\nIn 1938, gunmen barged into Reuther's apartment in an attempt to kidnap and murder the labor leader. The criminals were thwarted by a small group of Reuther friends and relatives. Nobody was injured.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://reuther100.wayne.edu/bio.php?pg=3|title=Walter P. Reuther|website=reuther100.wayne.edu|access-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Eleanor Roosevelt, Bessie Hillman, Jacob Potofsky, and Walter Reuther in New York City - NARA - 195505.jpg|thumb|Eleanor Roosevelt, Bessie Hillman, Jacob Potofsky, and Walter Reuther in New York City, January 7, 1957.|left]]On April 20, 1948, Reuther barely survived a double-barrel shotgun blast that ripped through his kitchen window as he was preparing a late evening snack. As the gunshot went off at 9:48&nbsp;p.m. E.S.T.,<ref name=\"United Press 1948, page 2\">United Press, \u201cReuther Shot in Detroit Home - Auto Union Official Victim of Ambush,\u201d ''The San Bernardino Daily Sun'', San Bernardino, California, Wednesday April 21, 1948, Volume LIV, Number 201, page 2.</ref> Reuther happened to turn toward his wife, and was hit in his right arm instead of the chest and heart.<ref>Pietrusza, David, 1948: Harry Truman's Improbable Victory and the Year That Transformed America, Union Square Press, 2011, p. 153</ref> Four slugs of the type used to kill large game had shattered his right arm into 150 pieces of bone. Another slug pierced his back and exited out his stomach. The assailant \u201cfled in a bright red four-door Ford sedan, police said.\u201d<ref>United Press, \u201cUnknown Assailant Wounds Reuther, Auto Union Head - Labor Leader Hit in Arm, Shoulder  by Shotgun Blast Through Kitchen Window,\u201d ''The San Bernardino Daily Sun'', San Bernardino, California, Wednesday April 21, 1948, Volume LIV, Number 201, page 1.</ref> Reuther, who did not lose consciousness, cursed his attacker as he was initially being treated by his next-door-neighbor, a doctor, as he lay on the kitchen floor. \u201c\u2018Those dirty sons of bitches!\u2019 Reuther cried. \u2018They have to shoot a man in the back. They won\u2019t come out in the open and fight.\u2019\u201d<ref name=\"United Press 1948, page 2\"/>  As doctors fought to save his life, he became infected with malaria and hepatitis from blood transfusions. Through months of therapy, he regained partial use of his right arm, but for the rest of his life had to train himself to write and shake with his left hand.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Reuther|last=Frank|first=Cormier|date=1970|publisher=Prentice-Hall|others=Eaton, William J|isbn=9780137793143|location=Englewood Cliffs, N.J|pages=[https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/155 155\u201356]|oclc=91809|url=https://archive.org/details/reuther00corm/page/155}}</ref> When Attorney General, [[Tom C. Clark|Tom Clark]], requested [[J. Edgar Hoover]] to get the FBI to investigate the shooting, Hoover refused, stating, \"I'm not going to send in the FBI every time some nigger woman gets raped.\"<ref name=\"Raskin\"/><ref>{{Cite book|title=The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW : a memoir|last=Reuther |first= Victor G.|date=1978|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=9780395275153|edition=  UAW special |location=Boston|pages=281|oclc=26295254}}</ref> The shooting was never solved.\nThirteen months after the attack, Reuther's brother Victor was almost killed by a similar shooting from a double-barrel shotgun. The blast traveled through his living room window and hit him in the face, throat, and chest. Victor's right eye had been shot out and had to be removed.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The brothers Reuther and the story of the UAW : a memoir|last=Reuther |first= Victor G.|date=1978|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=9780395275153|edition=  UAW special |location=Boston|pages=484\u201386|oclc=26295254}}</ref> Victor said, \"The attack on me was a way of serving notice to Walter. 'We didn't get you yet, but we're still around.'\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/10 10]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/10}}</ref> The shooting of Victor was also never solved.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the world together : my father Walter Reuther, the liberal warrior|last=Reuther.|first=Dickmeyer, Elisabeth|date=2004|publisher=LivingForce Pub|isbn=9780975379219|location=Lake Orion, Mich.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/11 11\u201313]|oclc=57172289|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/06/05/us/victor-reuther-influential-labor-leader-dies-at-92.html|title=Victor Reuther, Influential Labor Leader, Dies at 92|last=Saxon|first=Wolfgang|date=June 5, 2004|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 18, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of both shootings, [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] wrote: \"It seems unthinkable that the police have never been able to discover who shot Walter Reuther and because of that, in all probability, the same person perhaps has felt he could get away with shooting another brother. . . . [W]e have a right to protect men who are working in the interests of their fellow men.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=She was one of us : Eleanor Roosevelt and the American worker|last=Brigid.|first=O'Farrell|date=2010|publisher=ILR Press|isbn=9780801448805|location=Ithaca, N.Y.|pages=144|oclc=732957167}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nOn May 9, 1970, Walter Reuther, his wife May, architect [[Oscar Stonorov]], Reuther's bodyguard William Wolfman, the pilot and co-pilot were killed when their chartered [[Learjet 23]] crashed in flames at 9:33&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Time]]. The plane, arriving from Detroit in rain and fog, was on final approach to [[Pellston Regional Airport]] in [[Pellston, Michigan|Pellston]], Michigan, near the UAW's recreational and educational facility at [[Black Lake (Michigan)|Black Lake, Michigan]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/0901.html |title=Reuther Dies in Jet Crash With Wife and 4 Others |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=May 11, 1970 |accessdate=October 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.planecrashinfo.com/famous1970s.htm planecrashinfo.com Famous People Who Died in Aviation Accidents: 1970s]</ref> The [[National Transportation Safety Board]] discovered that the plane's [[altimeter]] was missing parts, some incorrect parts were installed, and one of its parts had been installed upside down,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1971/02/19/page/21/article/tie-faulty-altimeter-to-reuthers-death |title=Tie Faulty Altimeter to Reuther's Death  |date=February 19, 1971 |website=archives.chicagotribune.com |publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]] |access-date=July 11, 2016}}</ref> leading some to speculate that Reuther may have been murdered.<ref>See Michael Parenti, \"The Wonderful Life and Strange Death of Walter Reuther,\" Dirty Truths (City Lights Books, 1996), page 201.</ref> Reuther had been subjected earlier to two attempted assassinations.\n\n== Personal life ==\nWalter and May Reuther were married on March 13, 1936, after meeting on a streetcar in Detroit only six weeks earlier.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the World Together: My Father Walter Reuther, the Liberal Warrior|last=Dickmeyer, Reuther|first=Elisabeth|publisher=Living Force|year=2004|isbn=9780975379219|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/36 36-37]|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/36}}</ref> They had two daughters, Linda born in 1942 and Elisabeth in 1947.\n\nReuther led a simple, austere lifestyle. He neither smoked nor drank alcohol because he felt it sapped a person's vitality. For his daily lunch in his office he had the same menu: a sandwich and a cup of tea. He was an early riser. Author [[William Manchester]] wrote that Reuther's associates saw him as a \u201ctrue [[Asceticism|ascetic]].\u201d<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the World Together: My Father Walter Reuther, the Liberal Warrior|last=Dickmeyer, Reuther|first=Elisabeth|publisher=Living Force Publishing|year=2004|isbn=9780975379219|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/141 141]|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/141}}</ref>\n\nTo relax he liked to hike, fish and play tennis. His favorite music was German Lieder, Classical, Negro Spirituals and Union Songs. Although sometimes perceived as rigid with no sense of humor, Walter\u2019s colleague and friend [[Irving Bluestone]] said: \u201cThat wasn't true at all. He was a very easy person to work with and be with. He had a good sense of humor and could laugh at himself. And occasionally, when he was excited enough, he would use profanity just like anyone else coming out of the shop.\u201d<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the World Together: My Father Walter Reuther, the Liberal Warrior|last=Dickmeyer, Reuther|first=Elisabeth|publisher=Living Force|year=2004|isbn=9780975379219|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/340 340]|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/340}}</ref>\n\nReuther enjoyed being and working outdoors in nature. Whether building a fish ladder for the trout underneath their bridge or planting a [[Japanese garden|Japanese Garden]] for May that she could view outside their bedroom window, he enjoyed and relaxed by working on outdoor projects on his Paint Creek property, located outside [[Rochester, Michigan]]. He and his daughter Lisa planted an [[arboretum]], including over 50 types of tree, at their Paint Creek home. He was an expert woodworker and built much of the furniture for their home with his own hands. After the assassination attempt in 1948, which shattered his arm in 150 pieces, he rehabilitated his arm by squeezing a hard rubber ball and pushing out the walls to build their Paint Creek home from what had been a one-room cottage. He remarked, \u201cI got a good house and a good hand, all for the same money.\u201d<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the World Together: My Father Walter Reuther, the Liberal Warrior|last=Dickmeyer, Reuther|first=Elisabeth|publisher=Living Force Publishing|year=2004|isbn=9780975379219|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/115 115-117]|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/115}}</ref>\n\nMay was Walter's sounding board and close advisor throughout his public life. May was a teacher and involved in organizing a teachers\u2019 union. Early on she was making $60 a week of which she gave most to help organize auto workers into the fledgling UAW. She soon gave up her teaching career to become Walter's full-time secretary, earning $15 per week. She was active in many charities and programs to uplift the community.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Brothers Reuther and the Story of the UAW|last=Reuther|first=Victor G.|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|year=1978|isbn=9780395275153|location=|pages=127}}</ref> May marched side-by-side with Walter in the civil rights struggles in Selma and elsewhere. She hosted [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] at their Paint Creek home.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Putting the World Together: My Father Walter Reuther, the Liberal Warrior|last=Reuther Dickmeyer|first=Elisabeth|publisher=Living Force|year=2004|isbn=9780975379219|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/195 195]|url=https://archive.org/details/puttingworldtoge0000dick/page/195}}</ref> She also served as president of the PTA at their daughter's school.<ref name=\":3\" /> After the assassination attempt on Walter's life in 1948, May decided to spend most of her time at home trying to give their two daughters as normal a life as possible; although, the family had bodyguards and attack dogs living with them the rest of their lives.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Honors and awards ==\n[[File:ABOUT-ReutherTall-600.jpg|thumb|Walter Reuther statue located at the Walter and May Reuther UAW Family Education Center in Black Lake, Michigan.]]\n\n* President [[Bill Clinton]] awarded Reuther the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] posthumously in 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=50577|title=William J. Clinton: Remarks on Presenting the Presidential Medal of Freedom|website=www.presidency.ucsb.edu|access-date=February 28, 2018}}</ref>\n* Walter Reuther appears in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine's list of the 100 most influential people of the 20th century.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,26473,00.html|title=TIME 100 Persons of The Century|date=June 6, 1999|work=Time|access-date=February 28, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0040-781X}}</ref>\n* Reuther was inducted into the [[United States Department of Labor|Department of Labor's]] Hall of Honor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dol.gov/general/aboutdol/hallofhonor/1990_reuther|title=Hall of Honor Inductee: Walter P. Reuther|date=December 9, 2015|work=United States Department of Labor|access-date=March 20, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n* Reuther received the [[Eugene V. Debs Award]] in 1968 for his work in Industrial Unionism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://debsfoundation.org/index.php/landing/eugene-v-debs-award/|title=Eugene V. Debs Award|last= |date=September 18, 2017|website=Eugene V. Debs Foundation Website|publisher=Eugene V. Debs Foundation}}</ref>\n* The National Committee for Israel Labor gave Reuther the Histadrut Humanitarian Award in 1958.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jta.org/1958/06/18/archive/president-of-united-automobile-workers-union-gets-histadrut-award|title=President of United Automobile Workers Union Gets Histadrut Award {{!}} Jewish Telegraphic Agency|website=www.jta.org|language=en-US|access-date=March 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* The [[Weizmann Institute of Science]] in 1968 gave Reuther the Weizmann Award in the Sciences and Humanities<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wis-wander.weizmann.ac.il/weizmann-award-sciences-and-humanities|title=Weizmann Award in the Sciences and Humanities \u2013 News, Features and Discoveries from the Weizmann Institute of Science|date=November 1, 1999|work=Weizmann Wonder Wander|access-date=February 28, 2018|language=en}}</ref> and established the Walter P. Reuther Chair of Research in the Peaceful Uses of Atomic Energy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weizmann.ac.il/acadaff/Scientific_Activities/2007/Chairs.html|title=Scientific Activities: Weizmann Professorial Chairs, CDC's and Fellowships|website=www.weizmann.ac.il|access-date=February 28, 2018}}</ref>\n* Reuther received honorary degrees from, among other institutions, [[Harvard University]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oasis.lib.harvard.edu/oasis/primo?id=hua04003#container_3_25|title=Honorary Degree Recipients, June 12, 1969|last=|first=|date=|website=Harvard University|access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> [[University of Michigan]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://president.umich.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2014/06/Honorary-Degrees-1836-Present-1.pdf|title=Honorary Degrees Awarded 1836\u2013Present|last=|first=|date=|website=University of Michigan|access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> [[Oakland University]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oakland.edu/Assets/Oakland/provost/files-and-documents/Honorary-Degree/Honorary%20Degree%20Recipients_1963%20to%20Spring%202016.pdf|title=Honorary Degree Recipients 1963\u2013Present|last=|first=|date=|website=Oakland University|access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> [[Tuskegee University]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/59632339/|title=The Lincoln Star from Lincoln, Nebraska on June 1, 1965 \u00b7 Page 24|work=Newspapers.com|access-date=March 24, 2018|language=en}}</ref> and [[University of Rhode Island]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.uri.edu/commencement/honorary-degree-recipients/|title=Honorary Degree Recipients|website=web.uri.edu|language=en-US|access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref>\n* The Reuther-Chavez Award was created in 2002 by [[Americans for Democratic Action]] \"to recognize important activist, scholarly and journalistic contributions on behalf of workers' rights, especially the right to unionize and bargain collectively.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digitalcommons.ilr.cornell.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1378&context=articles|title=Labor's New Opening to International Human Rights Standards|last=Compa|first=Lance|date=|website=Digital Commons|access-date=March 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* The Walter P. Reuther Humanitarian Award was created in 1999 by [[Wayne State University]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wayne.edu/newsroom/release/1999/11/30/civil-rights-leader-lowery-to-receive-reuther-award-from-wayne-state-university-1317|title=Civil rights leader Lowery to receive Reuther Award from Wayne State University \u2013 Newsroom \u2013 Wayne State University|last=University|first=Wayne State|access-date=March 5, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n* There are three portraits and one sculpture of Reuther in the collection of the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian Institute's]] [[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://npg.si.edu/portraits/search|title=Portrait Search|language=en|access-date=March 20, 2018}}</ref>\n* Reuther appeared on the covers of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' Magazine twice, ''[[Newsweek]]'' three times, and ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine once.\n\n== Walter P. Reuther Humanitarian Award ==\n[[File:Reuther South.jpg|thumb|Walter P. Reuther Library, Wayne State University, Detroit, Michigan]]\nIn 1999, [[Wayne State University]], in collaboration with the UAW and the Reuther family, created the Walter P. Reuther Humanitarian Award to honor individuals who embody the spirit, vision, and values of Reuther.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://today.wayne.edu/news/1999/11/30/civil-rights-leader-lowery-to-receive-reuther-award-from-wayne-state-university-1317|title=Civil rights leader Lowery to receive Reuther Award from Wayne State University \u2013 Newsroom \u2013 Wayne State University|last=University|first=Wayne State|date=November 30, 1999|work=|access-date=October 27, 2019}}</ref> To date, the recipients of the award include civil rights activist [[Rosa Parks]], Congressman [[John Dingell]], civil rights activist [[Joseph Lowery]], UAW president [[Douglas Fraser]], and civil rights activist and Congressman [[John Lewis (civil rights leader)|John Lewis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://today.wayne.edu/news/2020/02/05/wayne-state-uaw-honor-civil-rights-legend-rep-john-lewis-35309|title=Wayne State, UAW honor civil rights legend Rep. John Lewis|last=|first=|date=February 5, 2020|website=Wayne State University|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Monuments ==\n[[File:I-696.svg|thumb|upright|Walter P. Reuther Freeway]]\n* [[Walter P. Reuther Library|Walter P. Reuther Library of Labor and Urban Affairs]], the largest labor archives in North America, located on the campus of [[Wayne State University]] in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]]\n* Walter Reuther Statue at Heritage Port, [[Wheeling, West Virginia]]. In Reuther's hometown, the seven foot statue is displayed outside the Convention Center alongside the [[Ohio River]] \n* [[Walter P. Reuther Freeway]] (I-696), stretching from the eastern to western suburbs of Detroit\n* Walter and May Reuther Family Education Center, [[Black Lake (Michigan)|Black Lake, Michigan]]\n* Walter Reuther Psychiatric Hospital, [[Westland, Michigan]]\n* Reuther Middle School, [[Rochester, Michigan]]\n* [[Walter Reuther Central High School]], [[Kenosha, Wisconsin]]\n\n== Archival records ==\nThe archival records of Reuther can be found mostly at the [[Walter P. Reuther Library|Walter P. Reuther Library of Labor and Urban Affairs]]. Notable are the ''UAW President's Office: Walter P. Reuther Records,'' an extensive collection that documents his time as President with the UAW. The materials include Reuther's personal correspondence, writings, photographs, official memorandum, and other various record types. Researchers are encouraged to contact the Reuther library for inquiries or access to materials. A guide to Reuther's archival materials can be found [http://reuther.wayne.edu/files/LR000261.pdf here].\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Biography|Organized labour}}\n*[[UAW|United Automobile Workers]]\n*[[AFL\u2013CIO|American Federation of Labor-Congress of Industrial Organizations]]\n*[[Americans for Democratic Action]]\n*[[Walter P. Reuther Library]]\n*[[List of civil rights leaders]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n'''Secondary sources:'''\n* Barnard, John. ''American Vanguard: The United Auto Workers during the Reuther Years, 1935\u20131970.'' Wayne State U. Press, 2004. 607 pp.\n* Boyle, Kevin. ''The UAW and the Heyday of American Liberalism, 1945\u20131968'' (1995)\n* Brattain, Michelle. \"Reuther, Walter Philip\"; [http://www.anb.org/articles/15/15-00570.html ''American National Biography Online'' Feb. 2000] Access March 21, 2015\n* Carew, Anthony. ''Walter Reuther'' (1993)\n* [[Kempton, Murray]]. \"The Reuther Brothers\" in ''Part of Our Time: Some Ruins and Monuments of the Thirties'' (1955, repr. 1998, repr. 2004)\n* Kornhauser, Arthur et al. ''When Labor Votes: A Study of Auto Workers'' (1956)\n* Goode, Bill. ''Infighting in the UAW: The 1946 Election and the Ascendancy of Walter Reuther'' (1994)\n* Parenti, Michael and Peggy Norton. ''The Wonderful Life and Strange Death of Walter Reuther'' (1996)\n* Zieger, Robert H. ''The CIO, 1935\u20131955'' (1995)\n* Reuther, Sasha, ''[[imdbtitle:1344811|Brothers on the Line]]'', Documentary (2012)\n\n'''Primary sources:'''\n*The [[Walter P. Reuther Library]], Archives of Labor and Urban Affairs on the campus of [[Wayne State University]] contains numerous collections related to Walter Reuther, most notably the [https://reuther.wayne.edu/node/2984 UAW President's Office: Walter P. Reuther Files], which \"reflect all phases of his career as president, UAW West Side Local 174 (1936); UAW Executive Board member (1936); director, UAW General Motors Department (1939\u201348); UAW vice-president (1942\u201346); UAW president (1946\u201370); president, ClO (1952\u201355); vice-president, AFL-CIO (1955\u201367); and president, AFL-CIO Industrial Union Department (1955\u201367).\"\n*Christman, Henry M. ed. ''Walter P. Reuther: Selected Papers'' (1961)\n*Reuther, Victor \"The Brothers Reuther and The Story of the UAW: A Memoir\" (1976)\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/0901.html Obituary], ''New York Times'', May 11, 1970\n* [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,989782,00.html ''Time Magazine'', Walter Reuther: Working-Class Hero]\n* {{Find a Grave|2262}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090325034818/http://www.airdisaster.com/reports/ntsb/AAR71-03.pdf NTSB Accident Report Number: NTSB-AAR-71-3]\n*[http://www.hrc.utexas.edu/multimedia/video/2008/wallace/reuther_walter.html Walter Reuther] interviewed by [[Mike Wallace]] on ''The Mike Wallace Interview'' January 25, 1958\n* [http://reuther100.wayne.edu/ The Reuther 100] Web site was established with IMLS grant money to commemorate the life of Walter P. Reuther on what would have been his 100th birthday.\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box|\n before= [[R. J. Thomas]] |\n title= President, [[United Auto Workers]] |\n