{"title_page": "Litzir\u00fcti", "text_new": "{{short description|Small village in Switzerland}}\n[[File:Litzir\u00fcti.jpg|thumb|right|Litzir\u00fcti]]\n'''Litzir\u00fcti''' is a small village in the [[Municipalities of Switzerland|municipality]] of [[Langwies]], in the [[Cantons of Switzerland|canton]] of [[Graub\u00fcnden]], [[Switzerland]].\n\nThe village effectively forms part of the [[Arosa]] (summer & winter) resort. The [[elevation]] is roughly 1,452 metres (4,764&nbsp;ft).\n\nThere is a railway station at Litzir\u00fcti, on the [[Rhaetian Railway#Arosa line (originally Chur-Arosa (ChA))|Chur-Arosa]] railway line: [[Litzir\u00fcti (Rhaetian Railway station)|Litzir\u00fcti]].\n\nThe [[Postal codes in Switzerland and Liechtenstein|postal code]] is 7058.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110706234824/http://www.litzirueti.ch/ Area website] {{in lang|de}}\n* [http://litzir\u00fcti.ch/ Holiday house website] {{in lang|de}}\n\n{{Coord|46.799|9.703|region:CH|display=title}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Litziruti}}\n[[Category:Villages in Graub\u00fcnden]]\n\n\n{{Graub\u00fcnden-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Small village in Switzerland}}\n[[File:Litzir\u00fcti.jpg|thumb|right|Litzir\u00fcti]]\n'''Litzir\u00fcti''' is a small village in the [[Municipalities of Switzerland|municipality]] of [[Langwies]], in the [[Cantons of Switzerland|canton]] of [[Graub\u00fcnden]], [[Switzerland]].\n\nThe village effectively forms part of the [[Arosa]] (summer & winter) resort. The [[elevation]] is roughly 1,452 metres (4,764&nbsp;ft).\n\nThere is a railway station at Litzir\u00fcti, on the [[Rhaetian Railway#Arosa line (originally Chur-Arosa (ChA))|Chur-Arosa]] railway line: [[Litzir\u00fcti (Rhaetian Railway station)|Litzir\u00fcti]].\n\nThe [[Postal codes in Switzerland and Liechtenstein|postal code]] is 7058.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110706234824/http://www.litzirueti.ch/ Area website] {{in lang|de}}\n* [http://litzir\u00fcti.ch/ Holiday house website] {{in lang|de}}\n\n{{Coord|46.799|9.703|region:CH|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Litziruti}}\n[[Category:Villages in Graub\u00fcnden]]\n\n\n{{Graub\u00fcnden-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Litzir%C3%BCti"}
{"title_page": "Princess Mar\u00eda Teresa of Bourbon-Parma", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish royal}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name = Princess Mar\u00eda Teresa\n| image = Mar\u00eda Teresa of Bourbon Parma (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Mar\u00eda Teresa in 1964\n| house = [[House of Bourbon-Parma|Bourbon-Parma]]\n| full name = Mar\u00eda Teresa Cecilia Zita Carlotta de Bourbon-Parma\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1933|07|28|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Paris]], [[French Third Republic]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2020|03|26|1933|07|28|df=yes}}\n| death_place = Paris, France\n| father = [[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Prince Xavier, Duke of Parma and Piacenza]]\n| mother = [[Madeleine de Bourbon-Busset]]\n| occupation = Professor\n}}\n'''Princess Mar\u00eda Teresa of Bourbon-Parma''' (28 July 1933 \u2013 26 March 2020) was a French-Spanish activist and academic. She was a member of the [[House of Bourbon-Parma]], a [[cadet branch]] of the [[Spanish royal family]]. She was a socialist activist, earning the nickname \"Red Princess\", and a [[monarchist]] who supported the [[Carlism|Carlist]] movement. She is the first royal to have died of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nMar\u00eda Teresa was born on 28 July 1933 in [[Paris]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.sg/royal-death-coronavirus-spain-princess-maria-teresa-borbon-parma-2020-3|title=A Spanish princess is the world's first royal to die from the coronavirus, Business Insider - Business Insider Singapore|last=Schild|first=Darcy|date=28 March 2020|website=www.businessinsider.sg|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> She was the daughter of [[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma, Duke of Parma and Piacenza]], a [[Carlist]] claimant to the [[Spanish throne]], and [[Madeleine de Bourbon-Busset]], a member of a [[cadet branch]] of the [[House of Bourbon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p11226.htm#i112254|title=Person Page|website=www.thepeerage.com|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref name=\"sathiya\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.sathiyasreesblog.com/2020/03/princess-maria-teresa-first-royal-to.html |title=Princess Maria Teresa First Royal to die from Coronavirus |date=28 March 2020 |website=Sathiyasreesblog |url-status=live |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> She was the younger sister of [[Princess Marie-Fran\u00e7oise of Bourbon-Parma|Princess Marie-Fran\u00e7oise]] and [[Carlos Hugo, Duke of Parma]], and an older sister of [[Prince Sixtus Henry of Bourbon-Parma|Prince Sixtus Henry]].\n\nShe grew up at the Old Bostz Castle, [[Besson, Allier|Besson]], [[Bourbonnais]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lamontagne.fr/moulins-03000/actualites/elle-avait-passe-son-enfance-au-chateau-de-bostz-a-besson-allier-la-princesse-maria-teresa-de-bourbon-parme-s-est-eteinte_13771245/|title=D\u00e9c\u00e8s - Elle avait pass\u00e9 son enfance au ch\u00e2teau de Bostz \u00e0 Besson (Allier) : la princesse Maria Teresa de Bourbon-Parme s'est \u00e9teinte|last=Delacou|first=Antoine|date=2020-03-28|website=www.lamontagne.fr|language=fr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> Having attended middle school in [[Tours]],<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.liberation.fr/planete/2014/07/23/maria-teresa-de-bourbon-parme-princesse-rouge_1069044|title=Maria-Teresa de Bourbon Parme. Princesse rouge|last=Launet|first=Edouard|date=2014-07-23|website=Lib\u00e9ration.fr|language=fr|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> she went on to obtain a doctorate in Hispanic studies from [[Paris-Sorbonne University]] and another doctorate in political sociology from the [[Complutense University of Madrid]]. She also studied [[Islam]] and how it related to [[women's rights]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Her 1977 thesis at the Sorbonne was entitled \"La clarificaci\u00f3n ideol\u00f3gica del Carlismo contempor\u00e1neo\" (\"Ideological clarification of contemporary Carlism\").<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/diario/1977/10/12/sociedad/245458817_850215.html|title=Mar\u00eda Teresa de Borb\u00f3n Parma|date=1977-10-12|work=El Pa\u00eds|access-date=2020-03-29|language=es|issn=1134-6582}}</ref>\n\n== Career and activism ==\nMar\u00eda Teresa was a professor at both of her alma maters.<ref name=\":2\" /> She was also a [[socialist]] activist and fought for women's rights.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nIn the 1960s and 1970s, Mar\u00eda Teresa supported her brother [[Carlos Hugo, Duke of Parma|Carlos Hugo]] in his fight to make the [[Carlist Party (1970)|Spanish Carlist party]] more liberal,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://royalcentral.co.uk/coronavirus/the-first-royal-dies-of-coronavirus-139794/|title=The first royal dies of coronavirus|date=2020-03-27|website=Royal Central|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> supporting an ideological shift in her family's Carlism.<ref name=\"EPobit\" /> Her royal roots and liberal socialist views attracted many personalities, leading her to meet [[Andr\u00e9 Malraux]], [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]], [[Yasser Arafat]] and [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]], and earned her the nickname of \"Red Princess\".<ref name=\"auto\" /> This nickname was used as the (Spanish) title of a 2002 biography of Mar\u00eda Teresa written by historian {{Interlanguage link|Josep Carles Clemente|lt=|es||WD=}}.<ref name=\"EPobit\">{{Cite web|url=https://elpais.com/gente/2020-03-27/muere-maria-teresa-de-borbon-y-parma-prima-del-rey-felipe-por-coronavirus.html|title=Muere Mar\u00eda Teresa de Borb\u00f3n y Parma, prima del rey Felipe, por coronavirus|last=Agencias|first=Silvia Ayuso|date=2020-03-27|website=EL PA\u00cdS|language=es|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1981, Mar\u00eda Teresa acquired Spanish nationality by [[Royal Decree-Law (Spain)|royal decree]]; the official state bulletin said that it was given \"at the request of the interested party and in response to the exceptional circumstances and her belonging to a family so closely linked to Spain\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/diario/1981/07/31/ultima/365378403_850215.html|title=Mar\u00eda Teresa de Borb\u00f3n|date=1981-07-31|work=El Pa\u00eds|access-date=2020-03-29|language=es|issn=1134-6582}}</ref>\n\nIn a 1997 interview, Mar\u00eda Teresa said that she was [[Christians|Christian]], but criticized some Christian attitudes to immigration that sought to create a divide.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/diario/1997/09/15/sociedad/874274402_850215.html|title=Entrevista \"El intercambio cultural es la vida de una civilizacil\u00f3n\"|date=1997-09-15|work=El Pa\u00eds|access-date=2020-03-29|language=es|issn=1134-6582}}</ref>\n\nMar\u00eda Teresa never married,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/royals/king-felipe-spain-relative-maria-teresa-first-royal-die-coronavirus/|title=King Felipe of Spain's Relative, 86, Becomes First Royal to Die from Coronavirus|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> and had no children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newidea.com.au/first-royal-maria-teresa-of-bourbon-parm-dies-from-coronavirus|title=JUST IN: First royal dies from coronavirus|website=New Idea|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> She was the aunt of [[Prince Carlos, Duke of Parma]].\n\nMar\u00eda Teresa was the first member of a [[royal family]] to die of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"sathiya\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/princess-becomes-worlds-first-royal-21771109|title=Princess becomes world's first royal to die from coronavirus|last=Bieber|first=Nicholas|date=March 28, 2020|website=mirror}}</ref> She died on 26 March 2020 in Paris, at the age of 86,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insider.com/royal-death-coronavirus-spain-princess-maria-teresa-borbon-parma-2020-3|title=A Spanish princess is the world's first royal to die from the coronavirus|last=Schild|first=Darcy|website=Insider|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> with a memorial service was held in [[Madrid]] on 27 March 2020, presided over by Rev. Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00f3n Garc\u00eda Gallardo, an officer of the [[Order of Prohibited Legitimacy]].<ref>{{cite web| url = https://carlismo.es/la-comunion-tradicionalista-ante-la-muerte-de-maria-teresa-de-borbon-parma/| title = La Comuni\u00f3n Tradicionalista ante la muerte de Mar\u00eda Teresa de Borb\u00f3n Parma| date = 27 March 2020| website = COMUNI\u00d3N TRADICIONALISTA| publisher = Carlist Traditionalist Communion| access-date = 2 April 2020}}</ref> A second  Catholic funeral was held on 2 April 2020 at the [[:fr:\u00c9glise Notre-Dame-des-Champs|Notre-Dame-des-Champs]] in Paris<ref>{{cite web| url = https://carlismo.es/ha-fallecido-maria-teresa-de-borbon-parma/| title = Ha fallecido Mar\u00eda Teresa de Borb\u00f3n Parma| date = 26 March 2020| website = COMUNI\u00d3N TRADICIONALISTA| publisher = Carlist Traditionalist Communion| access-date = 2 April 2020}}</ref> Her death was announced on the official website of the House of Bourbon-Parma.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.borboneparma.it/index.php/it/news-comunicazioni/461-reale-e-ducale-casa-di-borbone-parma|title=REALE E DUCALE CASA DI BORBONE PARMA|website=www.borboneparma.it|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nShe was the 4th cousin, once removed, of the current [[King of Spain]], [[Felipe VI of Spain|Felipe VI]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/uk/news/1135494/spanish-princess-becomes-the-first-royal-to-die-of-coronavirus-complications|title=Spanish Princess Becomes the First Royal to Die of Coronavirus Complications|date=28 March 2020|website=E! News|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n| boxstyle_1 = background-color: #fcc;\n| boxstyle_2 = background-color: #fb9;\n| boxstyle_3 = background-color: #ffc;\n| boxstyle_4 = background-color: #bfc;\n| boxstyle_5 = background-color: #9fe;\n| 1 = '''Maria Teresa of Bourbon-Parma'''\n| 2 = [[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Xavier, Duke of Parma]]\n| 3 = [[Madeleine de Bourbon-Busset]]\n| 4 = [[Robert I, Duke of Parma]]\n| 5 = [[Infanta Maria Antonia of Portugal]]\n| 6 = Georges de Bourbon, comte de Ligni\u00e8res\n| 7 = Marie Jeanne de Kerret de Quillien\n| 8 = [[Charles III, Duke of Parma]]\n| 9 = [[Louise Marie Th\u00e9r\u00e8se of Artois|Princess Louise of Artois]]\n| 10 = [[Miguel I of Portugal]]\n| 11 = [[Adelaide of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg|Princess Adelaide of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg]]\n| 12 = Henri de Bourbon, comte de Ligni\u00e8res\n| 13 = Adrienne de Mailly de Nesle\n| 14 = Ren\u00e9 de Kerret, vicomte de Quillien\n| 15 = Marie L\u00e9onie Gautier\n| 16 = [[Charles II, Duke of Parma]]\n| 17 = [[Maria Teresa of Savoy (1803\u20131879)|Princess Maria Teresa of Savoy]]\n| 18 = [[Charles Ferdinand, Duke of Berry]]\n| 19 = [[Marie-Caroline of Bourbon-Two Sicilies, Duchess of Berry|Princess Caroline of Naples and Sicily, Duchess of Berry]]\n| 20 = [[John VI of Portugal]]\n| 21 = [[Carlota Joaquina of Spain]]\n| 22 = [[Constantine, Hereditary Prince of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg|Constantine of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg]]\n| 23 = [[Princess Agnes of Hohenlohe-Langenburg]]\n| 24 = Eug\u00e8ne de Bourbon-Busset, comte de Ligni\u00e8res\n| 25 = Idalie de Calonne de Courtebonne\n| 26 = Adrien de Mailly, marquis de Nesle\n| 27 = Eug\u00e9nie Henriette de Lonlay\n| 28 = Charles-Fid\u00e8le de Kerret, vicomte de Quillien\n| 29 = Marie Marguerite Lefebvre de La Falu\u00e8re\n| 30 = Claude Joseph Gautier\n| 31 = Claudine Beno\u00eete Vespre\n}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{Cite book|title=El momento actual espa\u00f1ol, cargado de utop\u00eda|publisher=|year=1977|isbn=9788422902164|location=|pages=|language=es|last1=Borb\u00f3n-Parma|first1=Mar\u00eda Teresa de}}\n* {{Cite book|last1=Borb\u00f3n-Parma|first1=Mar\u00eda Teresa de|title=La clarificaci\u00f3n ideol\u00f3gica del partido Carlista|publisher=|year=1979|isbn=9788485596027|location=|pages=|language=es}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Cambios en M\u00e9xico|publisher=|year=1990|isbn=9788430918591|location=|pages=|language=es|last1=Borb\u00f3n-Parma|first1=Mar\u00eda Teresa de}}\n* {{Cite book|last1=Borb\u00f3n-Parma|first1=Mar\u00eda Teresa de|title=Magreb: Nuestro poniente proximo|publisher=|year=1994|isbn=9788476833308|location=|pages=|language=es}}\n* {{Cite book|last1=Borb\u00f3n-Parma|first1=Mar\u00eda Teresa de|title=Don Javier : una vida al servicio de la libertad|publisher=|year=1997|isbn=9788401530180|location=|pages=|language=es}}\n* {{Cite book|last1=Borb\u00f3n-Parma|first1=Mar\u00eda Teresa de|title=Desde T\u00e1nger|publisher=|year=1999|isbn=9788483740774|location=|pages=|language=es}}\n* {{Cite book|title=As\u00ed fueron, as\u00ed son|publisher=|year=2009|isbn=9788408088967|location=|pages=|language=es|last1=Borb\u00f3n-Parma|first1=Mar\u00eda Teresa de}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* {{Cite book|title=La Princesa Roja|publisher=|year=2002|isbn=9788427027930|location=|pages=|language=es|last1=Clemente|first1=Josep Carles|trans-title=The Red Princess}} (Biography)\n\n{{Princesses of Parma by birth}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bourbon-Parma, Maria Teresa}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Complutense University of Madrid alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in France]]\n[[Category:Paris-Sorbonne University alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Paris]]\n[[Category:Princesses of Bourbon-Parma]]\n[[Category:Spanish monarchists]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of French descent]]\n[[Category:Spanish women academics]]\n[[Category:Academics of the Complutense University of Madrid]]\n[[Category:Paris-Sorbonne University faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish women writers]]\n[[Category:Spanish women activists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Spanish women writers]]\n[[Category:Spanish women's rights activists]]\n[[Category:Spanish socialists]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Spanish Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:French monarchists]]\n[[Category:French women academics]]\n[[Category:20th-century French women writers]]\n[[Category:French women activists]]\n[[Category:21st-century French women writers]]\n[[Category:French women's rights activists]]\n[[Category:French socialists]]\n[[Category:French people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:French Christians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spanish royal}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name = Princess Mar\u00eda Teresa\n| image = Mar\u00eda Teresa of Bourbon Parma (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Mar\u00eda Teresa in 1964\n| house = [[Bourbon-Parma]]\n| full name = Mar\u00eda Teresa Cecilia Zita Carlotta de Bourbon-Parma\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1933|07|28|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Paris]], [[French Third Republic]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2020|03|26|1933|07|28|df=yes}}\n| death_place = Paris, France\n| father = [[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Prince Xavier, Duke of Parma and Piacenza]]\n| mother = [[Madeleine de Bourbon-Busset]]\n| occupation = Professor\n}}\n'''Princess Mar\u00eda Teresa of Bourbon-Parma''' (28 July 1933 \u2013 26 March 2020) was a French-Spanish activist and academic. She was a member of the [[House of Bourbon-Parma]], a [[cadet branch]] of the [[Spanish royal family]]. She was a socialist activist, earning the nickname \"Red Princess\", and a [[monarchist]] who supported the [[Carlism|Carlist]] movement. She is the first royal to have died of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nMar\u00eda Teresa was born on 28 July 1933 in [[Paris]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.sg/royal-death-coronavirus-spain-princess-maria-teresa-borbon-parma-2020-3|title=A Spanish princess is the world's first royal to die from the coronavirus, Business Insider - Business Insider Singapore|last=Schild|first=Darcy|date=28 March 2020|website=www.businessinsider.sg|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> She was the daughter of [[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma, Duke of Parma and Piacenza]], a [[Carlist]] claimant to the [[Spanish throne]], and [[Madeleine de Bourbon-Busset]], a member of a [[cadet branch]] of the [[House of Bourbon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p11226.htm#i112254|title=Person Page|website=www.thepeerage.com|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref name=\"sathiya\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.sathiyasreesblog.com/2020/03/princess-maria-teresa-first-royal-to.html |title=Princess Maria Teresa First Royal to die from Coronavirus |date=28 March 2020 |website=Sathiyasreesblog |url-status=live |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> She was the younger sister of [[Princess Marie-Fran\u00e7oise of Bourbon-Parma|Princess Marie-Fran\u00e7oise]] and [[Carlos Hugo, Duke of Parma]], and an older sister of [[Prince Sixtus Henry of Bourbon-Parma|Prince Sixtus Henry]].\n\nShe grew up at the Old Bostz Castle, [[Besson, Allier|Besson]], [[Bourbonnais]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lamontagne.fr/moulins-03000/actualites/elle-avait-passe-son-enfance-au-chateau-de-bostz-a-besson-allier-la-princesse-maria-teresa-de-bourbon-parme-s-est-eteinte_13771245/|title=D\u00e9c\u00e8s - Elle avait pass\u00e9 son enfance au ch\u00e2teau de Bostz \u00e0 Besson (Allier) : la princesse Maria Teresa de Bourbon-Parme s'est \u00e9teinte|last=Delacou|first=Antoine|date=2020-03-28|website=www.lamontagne.fr|language=fr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> Having attended middle school in [[Tours]],<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.liberation.fr/planete/2014/07/23/maria-teresa-de-bourbon-parme-princesse-rouge_1069044|title=Maria-Teresa de Bourbon Parme. Princesse rouge|last=Launet|first=Edouard|date=2014-07-23|website=Lib\u00e9ration.fr|language=fr|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> she went on to obtain a doctorate in Hispanic studies from [[Paris-Sorbonne University]] and another doctorate in political sociology from the [[Complutense University of Madrid]]. She also studied [[Islam]] and how it related to [[women's rights]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Her 1977 thesis at the Sorbonne was entitled \"La clarificaci\u00f3n ideol\u00f3gica del Carlismo contempor\u00e1neo\" (\"Ideological clarification of contemporary Carlism\").<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/diario/1977/10/12/sociedad/245458817_850215.html|title=Mar\u00eda Teresa de Borb\u00f3n Parma|date=1977-10-12|work=El Pa\u00eds|access-date=2020-03-29|language=es|issn=1134-6582}}</ref>\n\n== Career and activism ==\nMar\u00eda Teresa was a professor at both of her alma maters.<ref name=\":2\" /> She was also a [[socialist]] activist and fought for women's rights.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nIn the 1960s and 1970s, Mar\u00eda Teresa supported her brother [[Carlos Hugo, Duke of Parma|Carlos Hugo]] in his fight to make the [[Carlist Party (1970)|Spanish Carlist party]] more liberal,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://royalcentral.co.uk/coronavirus/the-first-royal-dies-of-coronavirus-139794/|title=The first royal dies of coronavirus|date=2020-03-27|website=Royal Central|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> supporting an ideological shift in her family's Carlism.<ref name=\"EPobit\" /> Her royal roots and liberal socialist views attracted many personalities, leading her to meet [[Andr\u00e9 Malraux]], [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]], [[Yasser Arafat]] and [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]], and earned her the nickname of \"Red Princess\".<ref name=\"auto\" /> This nickname was used as the (Spanish) title of a 2002 biography of Mar\u00eda Teresa written by historian {{Interlanguage link|Josep Carles Clemente|lt=|es||WD=}}.<ref name=\"EPobit\">{{Cite web|url=https://elpais.com/gente/2020-03-27/muere-maria-teresa-de-borbon-y-parma-prima-del-rey-felipe-por-coronavirus.html|title=Muere Mar\u00eda Teresa de Borb\u00f3n y Parma, prima del rey Felipe, por coronavirus|last=Agencias|first=Silvia Ayuso|date=2020-03-27|website=EL PA\u00cdS|language=es|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1981, Mar\u00eda Teresa acquired Spanish nationality by [[Royal Decree-Law (Spain)|royal decree]]; the official state bulletin said that it was given \"at the request of the interested party and in response to the exceptional circumstances and her belonging to a family so closely linked to Spain\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/diario/1981/07/31/ultima/365378403_850215.html|title=Mar\u00eda Teresa de Borb\u00f3n|date=1981-07-31|work=El Pa\u00eds|access-date=2020-03-29|language=es|issn=1134-6582}}</ref>\n\nIn a 1997 interview, Mar\u00eda Teresa said that she was [[Christians|Christian]], but criticized some Christian attitudes to immigration that sought to create a divide.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/diario/1997/09/15/sociedad/874274402_850215.html|title=Entrevista \"El intercambio cultural es la vida de una civilizacil\u00f3n\"|date=1997-09-15|work=El Pa\u00eds|access-date=2020-03-29|language=es|issn=1134-6582}}</ref>\n\nMar\u00eda Teresa never married,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/royals/king-felipe-spain-relative-maria-teresa-first-royal-die-coronavirus/|title=King Felipe of Spain's Relative, 86, Becomes First Royal to Die from Coronavirus|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> and had no children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newidea.com.au/first-royal-maria-teresa-of-bourbon-parm-dies-from-coronavirus|title=JUST IN: First royal dies from coronavirus|website=New Idea|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> She was the aunt of [[Prince Carlos, Duke of Parma]].\n\nMar\u00eda Teresa was the first member of a [[royal family]] to die of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"sathiya\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/princess-becomes-worlds-first-royal-21771109|title=Princess becomes world's first royal to die from coronavirus|last=Bieber|first=Nicholas|date=March 28, 2020|website=mirror}}</ref> She died on 26 March 2020 in Paris, at the age of 86,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insider.com/royal-death-coronavirus-spain-princess-maria-teresa-borbon-parma-2020-3|title=A Spanish princess is the world's first royal to die from the coronavirus|last=Schild|first=Darcy|website=Insider|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> with a memorial service was held in [[Madrid]] on 27 March 2020, presided over by Rev. Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00f3n Garc\u00eda Gallardo, an officer of the [[Order of Prohibited Legitimacy]].<ref>{{cite web| url = https://carlismo.es/la-comunion-tradicionalista-ante-la-muerte-de-maria-teresa-de-borbon-parma/| title = La Comuni\u00f3n Tradicionalista ante la muerte de Mar\u00eda Teresa de Borb\u00f3n Parma| date = 27 March 2020| website = COMUNI\u00d3N TRADICIONALISTA| publisher = Carlist Traditionalist Communion| access-date = 2 April 2020}}</ref> A second  Catholic funeral was held on 2 April 2020 at the [[:fr:\u00c9glise Notre-Dame-des-Champs|Notre-Dame-des-Champs]] in Paris<ref>{{cite web| url = https://carlismo.es/ha-fallecido-maria-teresa-de-borbon-parma/| title = Ha fallecido Mar\u00eda Teresa de Borb\u00f3n Parma| date = 26 March 2020| website = COMUNI\u00d3N TRADICIONALISTA| publisher = Carlist Traditionalist Communion| access-date = 2 April 2020}}</ref> Her death was announced on the official website of the House of Bourbon-Parma.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.borboneparma.it/index.php/it/news-comunicazioni/461-reale-e-ducale-casa-di-borbone-parma|title=REALE E DUCALE CASA DI BORBONE PARMA|website=www.borboneparma.it|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nShe was the 4th cousin, once removed, of the current [[King of Spain]], [[Felipe VI of Spain|Felipe VI]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/uk/news/1135494/spanish-princess-becomes-the-first-royal-to-die-of-coronavirus-complications|title=Spanish Princess Becomes the First Royal to Die of Coronavirus Complications|date=28 March 2020|website=E! News|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n| boxstyle_1 = background-color: #fcc;\n| boxstyle_2 = background-color: #fb9;\n| boxstyle_3 = background-color: #ffc;\n| boxstyle_4 = background-color: #bfc;\n| boxstyle_5 = background-color: #9fe;\n| 1 = '''Maria Teresa of Bourbon-Parma'''\n| 2 = [[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Xavier, Duke of Parma]]\n| 3 = [[Madeleine de Bourbon-Busset]]\n| 4 = [[Robert I, Duke of Parma]]\n| 5 = [[Infanta Maria Antonia of Portugal]]\n| 6 = Georges de Bourbon, comte de Ligni\u00e8res\n| 7 = Marie Jeanne de Kerret de Quillien\n| 8 = [[Charles III, Duke of Parma]]\n| 9 = [[Louise Marie Th\u00e9r\u00e8se of Artois|Princess Louise of Artois]]\n| 10 = [[Miguel I of Portugal]]\n| 11 = [[Adelaide of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg|Princess Adelaide of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg]]\n| 12 = Henri de Bourbon, comte de Ligni\u00e8res\n| 13 = Adrienne de Mailly de Nesle\n| 14 = Ren\u00e9 de Kerret, vicomte de Quillien\n| 15 = Marie L\u00e9onie Gautier\n| 16 = [[Charles II, Duke of Parma]]\n| 17 = [[Maria Teresa of Savoy (1803\u20131879)|Princess Maria Teresa of Savoy]]\n| 18 = [[Charles Ferdinand, Duke of Berry]]\n| 19 = [[Marie-Caroline of Bourbon-Two Sicilies, Duchess of Berry|Princess Caroline of Naples and Sicily, Duchess of Berry]]\n| 20 = [[John VI of Portugal]]\n| 21 = [[Carlota Joaquina of Spain]]\n| 22 = [[Constantine, Hereditary Prince of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg|Constantine of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg]]\n| 23 = [[Princess Agnes of Hohenlohe-Langenburg]]\n| 24 = Eug\u00e8ne de Bourbon-Busset, comte de Ligni\u00e8res\n| 25 = Idalie de Calonne de Courtebonne\n| 26 = Adrien de Mailly, marquis de Nesle\n| 27 = Eug\u00e9nie Henriette de Lonlay\n| 28 = Charles-Fid\u00e8le de Kerret, vicomte de Quillien\n| 29 = Marie Marguerite Lefebvre de La Falu\u00e8re\n| 30 = Claude Joseph Gautier\n| 31 = Claudine Beno\u00eete Vespre\n}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{Cite book|title=El momento actual espa\u00f1ol, cargado de utop\u00eda|publisher=|year=1977|isbn=9788422902164|location=|pages=|language=es|last1=Borb\u00f3n-Parma|first1=Mar\u00eda Teresa de}}\n* {{Cite book|last1=Borb\u00f3n-Parma|first1=Mar\u00eda Teresa de|title=La clarificaci\u00f3n ideol\u00f3gica del partido Carlista|publisher=|year=1979|isbn=9788485596027|location=|pages=|language=es}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Cambios en M\u00e9xico|publisher=|year=1990|isbn=9788430918591|location=|pages=|language=es|last1=Borb\u00f3n-Parma|first1=Mar\u00eda Teresa de}}\n* {{Cite book|last1=Borb\u00f3n-Parma|first1=Mar\u00eda Teresa de|title=Magreb: Nuestro poniente proximo|publisher=|year=1994|isbn=9788476833308|location=|pages=|language=es}}\n* {{Cite book|last1=Borb\u00f3n-Parma|first1=Mar\u00eda Teresa de|title=Don Javier : una vida al servicio de la libertad|publisher=|year=1997|isbn=9788401530180|location=|pages=|language=es}}\n* {{Cite book|last1=Borb\u00f3n-Parma|first1=Mar\u00eda Teresa de|title=Desde T\u00e1nger|publisher=|year=1999|isbn=9788483740774|location=|pages=|language=es}}\n* {{Cite book|title=As\u00ed fueron, as\u00ed son|publisher=|year=2009|isbn=9788408088967|location=|pages=|language=es|last1=Borb\u00f3n-Parma|first1=Mar\u00eda Teresa de}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* {{Cite book|title=La Princesa Roja|publisher=|year=2002|isbn=9788427027930|location=|pages=|language=es|last1=Clemente|first1=Josep Carles|trans-title=The Red Princess}} (Biography)\n\n{{Princesses of Parma by birth}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bourbon-Parma, Maria Teresa}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Complutense University of Madrid alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in France]]\n[[C